ook my own clothes back home to get washed and got what I took back - the week before.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 You got home every week did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
On the Sundays instead of going out to work in the field, I was only what - two and a half to three miles from home. It wasn\rquote t too bad, I could walk home an less than an hour. And back in time for the - cows at night again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 It wouldn\rquote t give you very long at home though?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
No. Oh no, but I had a worse place than that. I went to another farm - and - my wages - this was the last farm I went to. I would be at three farms altogether. I went to another farm where I had seven pound - for the six months.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 You had a year at your first farm?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 A year. With three pound and I can\rquote 
t remember what I had for the second half of the year, because you - you - you\rquote re engaged for six months in that time. Possibly I had three }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13318710\charrsid12015019 pound ten}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019  for the second month, but I had only three pound for the first six months, I can remember that. And then when I went to this next farm - I had seven p
ound - for six month, and that was in 1910 because I always remember that by - the year that King Edward died, we got a day off. We got a day off, except for looking after the cattle of course. We\rquote 
d to do all the work that - that was necessary, but we hadn\rquote t to go out into the fields. And I always remember - that - place that we got the day off because you got few - the days you got off were few and far between. The }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13318710\charrsid12015019 only day}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
 off that you usually got in - you were entitled to it, that was the - Rood Fair day
. The last - last - Wednesday in September, it was always - the last Wednesday in September, we got that day off, we were entitled to it. And - the March Fair, that was - these were the hiring fairs. And the March Fair -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Did you actually ever go to a hiring fair to get a job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 No. I - I -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 So you were saying you never needed to go to the hiring }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13318710\charrsid12015019 fairs}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
No, I never, but I went to the fairs all the same because it was a day off. And - and - aye, well that was two days in the year, it was only one -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Did you ever get Christmas off?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
Oh no, at Christmastime all the cattle were in, all these cattle had to be looked after. And - you couldn\rquote t get Christmas off but of course - it would be made like a Sunday, you wouldn\rquote t have to go out an
d into the fields to work. It - Christmas Day would be treated as a Sunday. But - but at that time New Year\rquote s Day was more looked on as a Scotch holiday than Christmas Day. Is yet I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 You said that you went to the second farm where you got seven pounds?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
Well - yes, well - I only stayed six month because - I never was settled at farm working, and I wanted a - job on an estate or something like that, that was what I always - fancied. But anyway I was at that farm for six months and I left ther
e and had to go and hire again, and this time the - the - the farmer - had sent word - with the farmer I was working and where I was leaving. He had heard that I was a good milker and - if you were a good milker - you could - get a bigger wage in those da
ys because all the farmers were beginning to - keep about - sixty and seventy cows. But this one that I went to - had a only thirty-one cows, and there was three of us to milk them. And I\rquote 
d milk ten - tonight, ten in the morning, and eleven at night, we took turn about. With the extra one. Well - what I\rquote m going to tell you about this - I had eleven pound five for my six months wages at this place, because I didn\rquote 
t want to go. I had arranged with a - friend to go to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Glasgow{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and see if we could get a job - on 
the railway. So when this word came the farmer came - home and told me about this other farmer, that wanted me, he had heard that I was a good milker. I says, oh but I\rquote m not going to hire. Oh well you\rquote 
ll have to turn up, he said, because he says, I\rquote ve - told him I would send you down, and if you don\rquote t go - he\rquote ll think I haven\rquote t - told you. Oh all right, I said, I\rquote 
ll go. So I went to my friend and I told him, and he says - oh - soon get out of that. Ask him for a wage that you - you know he\rquote ll not give you. And I says, how much would that be? Oh, he says, ask him for eleven pound ten, he\rquote 
ll never give you that. Oh all right. So I went down and waited \lquote til the milk was put on the train and he was down putting it on the train. And he came forward, are you the boy from - from Mr Morrison\rquote 
s? I said, yes. Oh, he says, I heard you were a good milker, so, he says - I\rquote m needing a boy just like you, what sort of wage would you want? Oh, I says, I would want eleven pound ten. Oh never on earth. He says, I\rquote ve never paid 
a wage like that in my life. I says, there\rquote s no harm done Mr McCartney, he says - I says, no harm and I got up on my bicycle to get away. Oh but, he says, stop a minute, he says, I thought about ten pound. No, I says, eleven pound ten or I\rquote 
m not coming. So he thought a minute, he says, I\rquote ll tell you what I\rquote ll do, I\rquote ll give you eleven pound five and five shillings Earls.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13318710\charrsid12015019 What\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019  that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 That was a binding - fee. Once you\rquote 
d accepted that what they called Earls - it was a binding fee, it was usually two shillings, but he gave me five shillings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 You would get that when you started?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 No, I got it there and then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 And the rest of the money when you were finished your six months?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Finished the six months. So I went home and - I said to my friend, I says, I
\rquote m getting eleven pound ten. Never on earth. Never on earth. I says, well there\rquote s the five shillings Earls, I says, and I\rquote ve got - I\rquote 
m getting eleven pound five. So I had to go. But believe me I worked for it, I was up at a quarter to five in the morning to put the cows in to start milking at five o\rquote clock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 How many cows were on this farm?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
Thirty-one I told you. No. This was the thirty-one cows where there was three of us to milk them and I took turn about at milking the odd one
. After we had milked them I went in and had my breakfast. Come out. This was 1911 - the hot dry year. It was. I - come out, put the cows in the field, washed out the byre, and we had a big boiler with whitewash on it - in it, and I got a can}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13318710\charrsid12015019  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 fu}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13318710\charrsid12015019 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 l of this 
and went over and - dabbed all the places where there was any - mark or anything because they were very particular in these dairies, an inspector came round periodically and had a look round to see if it was - when you were selling your milk. And after I 
had that done I was out into the field to do - whatever was doing. Potatoes. Planting potatoes, hoeing turnips, working at the hay, working at the harvest, gathering potatoes, shoring turnips or whatever was doing on the farm.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 So you were there the six months?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 I was there the six months.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 March \lquote til September were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
Twenty eighth of November. From the Twenty-eighth of May, to the twenty-eighth of November, these were the term days at that time. Nowadays - I think they\rquote re only engaged
 by the month. You can leave in a month if you like. But that was the rule in those days, from the twenty-eighth of May - to the twenty-eighth of November.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 You mentioned taking the milk down to the station?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Yes. As I say I worked in the farm all day. And went in at five o\rquote 
clock, put the cows in, milked them, went in and got my supper, come out, put the pony in the - milk cart, and - Mr McCartney helped me on the - on with the - the milk. Onto the cart, and I took it down to Lochmaben station and 
one week out of three I had to stay with other - another fellow. There were six of us took the milk to the station, and - I and another fellow put it on the ttain, one week in three. We took turn about at stopping and putting in the milk, the other two - 
other four - they just came and put their milk off at the - siding and away home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 They didn\rquote t wait for the train to come?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 No, they didn\rquote 
t. Two of us did it each week in turn. Went home - the train came past at half past seven, sometimes it was te
n minutes late. Put the milk on the train, went home - unyoked the poney and put it in the field. And practically had to go to bed to be able to get up at five in the morning again. Quarter to five in the morning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 What were the conditions like on that
 farm? What sort of accommodation did you have
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Oh I had a bothey to myself there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Was that normal? I thought normally all the workmen would be together?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 No. You see - they\rquote 
d a married ploughman and he lived in the cottage. And there was a man stayed in the house. He\rquote d - he\rquote d - been the son - of - farmers in Ayrshire who had died and everything was left to him but he - he wasn\rquote 
t - competent to look after a farm, so he came to this place, they were friends, they were no relation but - they were friends, and he came there and paid a pound a week for his keep, and did lots of odd jobs about the farm as well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 They had a bargain there surely then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
Aye, they had a bargain there. Well - as I told you - in 1911, it was a hot dry year and the milk wasn\rquote t keeping very well, and we}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7866099\charrsid12015019 \rquote d}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019  came that the milk had to be taken to Dockerby station and put on the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7866099\charrsid12015019 train}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019  - no, I beg your pardon, I\rquote ve made a mistake there. The milk did go to Pitlochry from Lachmaben, but it was - Pitlochry, that\rquote s a big cr
eamery there seemingly. But - the milk wasn\rquote 
t keeping. So what had - to be done was the order came out that the milk had to be taken to Lockerbie creamery and they made it into cheese before it went bad, it being this hot dry weather. Well the six weeks th
at it went - through the day, the farmer put this man on, this - man that paid the pound a week to take it to Locherbie. And that would have been a grand job for me wouldn\rquote 
t it? But no, I was more used on the farm, out in the fields. So anyway, the six wee
ks went past. And - the order came that the milk was to be put onto the train at Locherbie station again, to go to Pitlochry. So - after the milking was passed and I had my supper - I put the pony in the trap - took it up to the dairy where the milk was a
ll - cooled over a refrigerator that run - run over this refrigerator and cooled, and the farmer helped me to put it on the cart and - he said, there you are then Bob, run it down to the station. I says, no, no. I says, run it down yourself, or get }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13318710\charrsid12015019 however}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019  you likes to take it, I\rquote 
m not taking it. I says, get - Willie Heslop to take it down, and they couldn\rquote t ask him to take it at night, he wouldn\rquote t have done it. So that meant the farmer had to go himself. So he went with his milk to Lochmaben station that ni
ght and put it on the train, and come back with a pipe, and an ounce of tobacco to get round me. But he was a nice fellow, you couldn\rquote t - you - I mean - I couldn\rquote t anyway, I couldn\rquote t - stick out with him, he\rquote 
d asked me when I engaged with him he says, if I want to go anywhere in the evening, he says, you wouldn\rquote 
t mind running the milk down to Lochmaben station for me? Oh, I says, not at all. But I - I - I got it to do regularly. But he run it periodically after that. And - just when he wanted to go anywhere he asked me to take it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Was he a nice man to work for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Oh he was, he\rquote s away in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Canada{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} now. Aye, he\rquote s - his mother and sister - and his wife - run the farm, when I was with them, but they were all dead, they were - his wife and his - no, his sis
ter married - a Thorneywhit - Gibson of Thorneywhit. And - his wife died and his mother died. And he was left on his own, so his lease at that farm was - ended and he took another farm, Lochbrow, away up a - above where you live. And that was the last tim
e I saw him, I was going cycling up to her home - when I met Willie McCartney coming down into the town and he jumped off his bike, I hadn\rquote 
t seen him for ages so he shook hands and asked me where I - where I was now, well I was at I was at Highfield then.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
What sort of relationship was there between you, was it definitely a master and a servant, or did you work together rather?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
Oh it was master and servant, I mean they had - they had their meals - in a room, and I just had to have my food in the - in the kitchen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Did all the men eat together there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 There were - nobody but me. I was the only one. I was the only one there.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 On the first farm you were on there was more than one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Well - no, no, they - the old man - and - the servan
t girl and I had our food in the kitchen, and - and the rest had their - food in the room. The boss and his brother and his sister and their mother, all had their food down the room.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 How about the second farm you were on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 The second farmer was o
n well - there was three of us there, there was the - single ploughman and the old man and me, I was only cowboy or - helping the - the man helping the - the man they called the bullock man, there was this man }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13318710\charrsid12015019 looked}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019  after all the cattle in the yard, but I
 had - I had to look after the four cows here. And he - looked after all the feeding - there was feeding - bullocks, and there was a lot of younger cattle I had to look after them and help him with them. So the three of us, the - the old boy - and the - s
i
ngle poloughman and I - had - had our food in the kitchen. Well - the servant girl I suppose would have to have hers with us too but she never seemed to have her food with us, she just used to have it before we went in or - or - or after - we never - she 
never sat down at the table with us anyway. But the first night I went there - I often think about it yes, as we walked in - the single }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7866099\charrsid12015019 p}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 loughman went first, then John Scott - second and me third. And he turned to me and he says - Bob - you\rquote ll thrive here, it\rquote s oatmeal dumpling fourteen times a week.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 What was the food like in the different places?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Good plain food, it was quite good plain food. But - what bowls of }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13318710\charrsid12015019 porridge}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
 they used to set us out. And this is what made this - John Scott - he said, oatmeal dumpling fourteen times a week. Porridge. Porridge.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Was this to fill you up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
Aye, this was supposed to fill - and it did, it filled you up at the time but it didn\rquote t sustain you long. That\rquote s the trouble. It was quite good plain food.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Did you get meat every day? You were telling me about that rabbit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
Oh that was a different place. Rabbits. Oh we got meat pretty regular. But - where - where the - reared a lot of sheep - there was some - trouble - that sheep - seemed to take - it 
was - they called them sturdies, they got - giddy and - well when - when a farmer saw that, if he - he bled it. It was as good as mutton that you buy in the butchers. But if that - sheep died through the night and the blood run through its body - it wasn
\rquote t as good as it would have been if they\rquote 
d been - bled when it died first, yes. And they called it braxy. You ever hear tell of braxy? Well that was what they called it, and of course all these sheep - were eaten on the farm because I mean they - couldn\rquote t sell them, the butchers wouldn
\rquote t buy them. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 So it wasn\rquote t really all that palatable?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
Well, when they were bled - bled - it was as good as mutton. But when the blood got through them - the meat didn\rquote t look so nice.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 You got two decent meals in the day did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Three.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 You had your breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
Breakfast, dinner and - and supper. And in the har - hay and harvest time you got tea in the afternoon sent out to the field. That was so you\rquote d work two hours or three hours later at nigh
t. But we used to en - enjoy the harvesting, if it was good weather, but if it was bad weather, oh it was - a miserable job, I re - I remember this first place that I was in. Mr Wilson come out and he says, well boys, it\rquote 
s a nice morning, go and - what you call - cope the stoops. Pull them over. With their bottoms to the sun and the wind, to dry them, and he says, we\rquote ll put - this was a twenty acre field, and we\rquote 
ll put it in in the afternoon. So out we went. Charlie Mowbray, Joe and his father, Joe Mobbray, Coid, the - single man, and myself. And - a woman, I can\rquote 
t remember who the woman was that came and worked in the harvest. We went and we upset all these - stooks in a twenty acre field, come in and had our dinner. And then on came the rain. And out would come Mr Wilson, well boys - it\rquote 
s hopeless, just go and set them all up again. And that happened two or three times before we got these - before we finally got them gathered in, it ended up in making them into - to - what was it they call them, stamp-coles
, little stamp-coles. You gathered them - you gathered them together, and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13318710\charrsid12015019 you put - a stook - five - sheave}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 s in and then built them on and built them on until you got them to a top and put one round as a sort of thatch. And that kept the hedge at the corn 
dry. Well that was the way we ended up putting that field then. Hutches, they called them hutches. And that field got hutched in the finish, and later we got a decent day and then of course - we carted it into the shed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Did you ever have much to do with horses?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 No, I never had anything to do with horses in that place. There\rquote s -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
Where did you go after you were finished in there? Your eleven pound ten farm, what was the name of that one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 It was Small Rig. But - where could I go? Where c
ould I go but to - coming in at half past eight at night? I had to get up a quarter to five in the morning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 After you were finished working there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
Oh where did I go after that place? Well it was shortly after that I went to High Field, to the - 
the - the solicitor and Town Clerk in Locherbie heard tell of me and he wrote to my father to see if I would go - to him, to look after a pony in the garden. So I thought, oh this is - just the job, this is more in my line than working on a farm. So I wen
t with my father to him and - I engaged to go to him. For thirty }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13318710\charrsid12015019 shillings}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019  a month. And all found.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 That\rquote s less than you were getting on the farm?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
It was, it was less than - but my father pointed out that - I might get a better place out of it and - so I did really. I got - the first - I worked there in the summer months, and - I\rquote 
d only engaged for the summer months. But I got a better job in the meantime - there was a bacon curer down at the foot of the village where I lived. And - the boy - that 
had worked there had taken measles and he went home with the measles and - he got up and went out too early and - it turned into pneumonia and he died. Well after I was engaged to go to this place for the thirty shillings a week - a month - Mr Underwood t
he bacon curer came to see if I would go in his place. And he says, you can either come and live down there or you can live at home but you can have all your food down there and I\rquote 
ll give you ten shillings a week. So I wanted to stick to this job because it was ten shillings a month more than - it was more than ten shillings a month because - there\rquote s more weeks in the year - than ten shilling - I mean ten shillings a month.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Ten shillings a week works out at more than thirty bob a month?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 It - it wo
rks at out at twenty-six pound a year. Ten shillings a week. And he pay - I can always remember he paid me with a golden sover - a half sovereign each Saturday, and I wanted to stay here but my father wouldn\rquote t let me, he says, no, no, he says, you
\rquote re engaged to go to there, he says, you\rquote ll have to go. So I had to go to this place but oh I never regretted it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 What did you have to do at the bacon curer\rquote s then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
Well - it - the - the man that did the bacon curing - John French was his name. You couldn\rquote t have got a better teacher, he was so patient, I mean - if you were making a mistake he would just say, no, bob, that\rquote s not the way I showed you I
\rquote ll show you again. And he - he\rquote d the patience of Job. \lquote Til I got that I could do it as well as him. Well I helped all day, doing that and on the - on the Friday - Saturday, on the Saturday, I\rquote 
d to go with the bacon - Mr Underwood went on the Thursday market day and went round the shops in Lockerbie and got orders for the bacon and I had to go and deliver it on the Saturday morning round the shops, McKenzies, McJerrow\rquote 
s and - all the different shops in Locherbie, and after I had that done I had to go to the gas works and load up this cart with coke.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 That\rquote s what you used for the curing was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Yes, that was used for the hams and that for curing hams. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 What did you have to do then, did you have to light the boiler or something?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
No, Mr French attended to that, it was a - a brazier, he used to light this brazier and let it burn up, outside, \lquote 
til the - the most of the smoke got away and it was all brown, all red. And then I helped him to carry it in and shut the doors, and that -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Did he just leave that in the room with the carcasses hanging round about?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 In the room where all the h
ams were - all the hams were singing - hanging along the joists. You see, there was joists in this and - room above I expect and - and all these joists had hooks right along, and hams hanging on them all along and we put this brazier in and there it - sta
yed for a - \lquote til it went out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Did you have to salt them at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
No, I never had to do it but - of course Mr French attended to all these odd jobs. I - I had to - help roll the bacon you know, roll it into sides. And - and tie it with string, and round again and rope - loop and then - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13318710\charrsid12015019 round again}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
, and finish it off and then you had a ham perhaps as long as that, a little thicker at that end than it was at this end. And these were what I took, and then put a net over it, and that was what I took to 
the shops on the Saturday morning. Well I - I would like to have stayed there because they were such nice people and I got on so well with them all. But my father insisted that I went to - to -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Did you eat with them or did you go home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Beg pardon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Did you eat with them? You said that they offered to feed you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 I ate with them. Yes, I ate with them.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 You would eat rather well there I should think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Oh they didn\rquote t eat the bacon. They\rquote 
d have it for their breakfast I expect, we had it for our breakfast but - but - oh I lived pretty well there, but I did at the next place that I went to too, because we just got what they had down the room.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 This is Highfield?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Aye. We - we got just what they had in - in their home and we -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 What sort of staff did they have there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 A governess - they\rquote 
d a governess and two maids and me. And - when - after I had this - six months in, I expected my - engagement was finished and I would have to go and hunt another job, and that was what 
I was vexed about giving up this job for at the bacon curing because it was filled by now. And that was what I was vexed about. However - Mr McJerrow came to me and said - that if I would stay on with them - he would take on another piece of ground, and m
ake it into a tennis court and a garden, and it would be }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13318710\charrsid12015019 a permanent}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019  job for me. I said, oh well - I - if you give me more money I\rquote ll be quite pleased to say. So, oh yes, I\rquote ll give you more money but - it wasn\rquote t much more.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 What did it go up to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 I think it went up to thirty-five shillings a month. Instead of thirty.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 But you were quite well looked after?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Oh yes. Pretty well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Where did you get to sleep there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 I had a bothey there too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 I thought you would have been in the house there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
No, I had a bothey there too. It was above the garage. But what I liked about it after - I agreed to stay on with them with the thirty-five months he came to me - thirty-five shillings a month, he - he came to me, well Robert, he says - I - I\rquote 
m going to have a motor car, so, he says, would you like to drive? I says, oh yes, I would like to drive. Well I\rquote 
ll send you for six months to the garage, to learn - driving. So I went into the Crown works at Locherbie, Hunter and Gardener was the people that run it in those days. And I was there - the six months.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Did Mr McJerrow give you your pay when you were at the garage?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
Oh yes. I got my pay. My pay went on just the same as in the garage but I don\rquote t think it would cost him anything for 
teach - for having me taught to drive because he had he had - a big interest in the - in the garage. He had a big in - you see, he had his money invested in the garage so I expect they would just have to - teach me to drive for nothing but - they were int
o pocket because I did nothing but wash cars for weeks.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 When you were working in the garage where did you stay?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
I stayed at Highfield, oh aye, down - down to the bothey and got my food there. Got my food at the house and went up - went up at nine o\rquote clock in the morn - eight o\rquote 
clock in the morning. And - stayed to - one. Went down and had my dinner, went back up at two. And stayed to five, unless there was something turned up that he couldn\rquote t let you away, I\rquote ve seen us having to go out to a - an ac
cident and bring the car in that was - was one night - one night I - I was at it \lquote til nine o\rquote clock, bringing this - wrecked car in. So that was where I - learned to drive the car and of course -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Did you have to sit a test in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 No. No, no, you hadn\rquote t to sit a test. Of course there wasn\rquote 
t so many cars on the road as there is now. Well - I mean to say it was - it was a different thing as thousands and thousands of cars on the road, that\rquote s what - when they started - making you have a test. 
But anyway - I - I was still working there and I had this pony. And the officers of the Kings Own Scottish Boarderers after me to see if I would go and look after Colonel Kerr\rquote s horse, you remember Colonel Kerr that was doctor - no, no, you wouldn
\rquote t. He wa
s doctor in Dunfries infirmary. He was the doc - he was the Colonel. Yes, Colonel Kerr, he was Colonel Kerr of the Kings Own Scottish Borderers, and Doctor Livingston, another doctor out of the infirmary was the medical officer for the Kings Own Scottish 
Borderers. And - this Leiutenant Douglas came to me to see if I would go and look after - Colonel Kerr\rquote s horse. So - oh no, I didn\rquote t want to do that because I wanted to - go and have a - a fortnight\rquote 
s holiday with my brother up in - Dalserf in Lanarkshire. 
So however he went and - Mr McJerrow sand - Mr McJerrow come down and he said - oh you out to join the Territorials Robert, I used to belong to the - the old Volunteers and I used to enjoy going to camp. So - Mr Douglas come down again. To see that - if I
 would go, and he says, you know - he says, if you join the Territorials, he says, you\rquote ll get a shilling a day for the fortnight you\rquote re at camp. And you\rquote ll get a sovereign from Colonel Kerr for looking after his horse, and you\rquote 
ll also get a pair of boots that\rquote ll come in useful for you working in the garden here. Well that was all money in those days you know. So he got round me and I went and - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13318710\charrsid12015019 joined}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019  the Territorials. The biggest mistake I ever did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 This was round about 1912 was it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 19 - yes, 19
12. So I went to the camp and I got what he said, the fourteen shillings for the shillings a day, and the sovereign from Colonel Kerr, and the pair of boots. And I came home and the next time - next - the following year - he came to me, to go again and lo
ok after the Colonel\rquote s horse and I says, no, no, I says, I haven\rquote t had a holiday I says since I came here, I said, I want to go and have a holiday with my brother. So I didn\rquote t go. But the - m}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13318710\charrsid12015019 y friend went and - the battalion}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019  came home on the Saturday night 
and I went up to the station to meet my friend and he says, we\rquote ve to hold ourselves }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13318710\charrsid12015019 in}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019  readiness, there\rquote s going to be a war. And he says, we\rquote ve got to hold ourselves in readiness for being called up for military service. So I thought, oh well, that means m
e too. Sure enough - war was declared on the fourth of August in 1914. And I had to go away to the army. Well - in the meantime - I was out with my - people, driving, and I met - the chauffeur - that was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13318710\charrsid12015019 chauffeur}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019  to the doctor\rquote s family, and they were both
 out for a picnic one afternoon, and this Willie Welsh, he said, to me, I wonder you don\rquote t join that Bob. I said, what is it? He says - I\rquote ve joined this - and I\rquote 
m liable to be called up if a war breaks out for the motor transport, but he says, I get four pounds a year for being a member and he says it keeps me in clothes. Well it - you cold get a good suit of clothes for three pound in those days. I says, I
\rquote m afraid I can\rquote t join that now because, I says, I\rquote m already a member of the Territorials. And I regre
tted it. Because when they were called up they got six shillings a day and I only got a shilling. And that would have been a big difference, well the - there\rquote 
s one man, he was called up along with this Willie Welsh and he come home - and he bought two buse
s, and started a bus service, Johnnie Robertson, you remember when he started the two buses. But the Caldonian - bus company were running buses between Locherbie and {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Dumfries{\*\xmlclose}
 at that time, and Johnnie Robertson started - running them cheaper than the Caledonian Bus Company. But it - immediately - he\rquote 
d started that the Caledonian came down sixpence cheaper than he did because of course they were running - buses - in all directions and they could afford to lose on that run until they - run him off the road. So Johnnie Robertson came down to a shilling.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 So what happened to him then, did he get run out of business?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 He did. They bought \lquote 
em off him in the finish, but they gave him a good job you remember, he was made manager of the Locherbie depot, and they bought him over, what he got for it I don\rquote 
t know but - it put him on his feet because he started contracting with lorries after that, running to different places with loads of stuff, as well as being manager of the bus company. So he did himself well out of that six shillings a day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 When did you go off to war then? As soon as it was official?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
Oh I went off at - that day. Well I met that - Willie Welsh that was with the doctor that said about the - the badge, in the morning I was up for my boss\rquote 
s paper and he was going round to his work, and - when I met him, he says, have you got your calling up papers yet? I said, no, not yet, but, I says, I\rquote 
ll expect them when I go down, I says, have you got yours? He says, no, but he says, I expect them when I go down for my breakfast. So sure enough my papers were there when I went down and I had to report at the drill hall at eleven o\rquote 
clock. And - we - met at the drill hall and we marched up to the Town Hall where Provost Byers, made a speech and we march
ed off from there to Dumfries, but coming up Main Street in Locherbie I met Willie Welsh coming down waving his papers, he had got his when he went home. Well would you believe it, I never clapped eyes on the Willie Welsh - from that day - \lquote 
til the days I was coming home, when I come home from }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13318710\charrsid12015019 Mesopotamia}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
 I was quarantined in - quarantined in one of the hospitals in London in case I had brought any disease home with me, for a fortnight, and after the fortnight was up I got a - paper to go down to Wellington
 Barracks to get a warrant to take me up to Kinross, and I had to go to Euston station and get that exchanged for a ticket and when I got there there }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13318710\charrsid12015019 was}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019  a queue - oh a queue of soldiers about ten yards long, waiting to get their tickets, and I fell into t
his queue and was marching up and I never noticed who was in front of me, but when it came his turn to ask for a ticket to - Kinross - I knew his voice, I says, mercy, Willie Welsh, and he turned - fancy meeting him. Very beginning and very end, we went u
p on the train together to Kinross and come down at night. Together.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Where did you go first when you went away?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 We went to -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 You say you went to Dufries?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 We went to Dumfries and then we were - sent up to 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Bannockburn{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. And what a place 
we were put into for billets. It had been an old mill and - the grease on the floor was about quarter inch thick and we had - sheets to put down. But the sheets were ruined the first morning, so of course they had - they couldn\rquote 
t keep us there. So they marched us from there to the mills at Tillicoultry. And we were in Tillicoultry for some time and did our drills there. And then the half of the battalion volunteered for foreign service, and the same happened in the 4}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\super\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019  KOSB, and they put the half - sent the
 half that had volunteered to make a foreign service battalion with the half of the 4}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\super\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019  KOSB and the half of the 4}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\super\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019  KOSB that didn\rquote t volunteer were sent to Tillicoultry to make a home service battalion.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 What did you do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Well I went to - to - to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Stirling
{\*\xmlclose}
 - with the - to the 4th KOSB. I went for overseas. But - while at Tillicoultry, they paraded us - in the field opposite, and told us to strip to the waist, Doctor Kerr, Colonel Kerr and Doctor Livingstone were coming to examine us for vaccination
s, so when they come to me I had no marks, and they said, where are your marks? I said, oh, I said, I was vaccinated twice in infancy but it never took, and the one turned to the other and said, this man\rquote 
s immune from smallpox. Well I was sent off - to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Stirling{\*\xmlclose}
, and we were - paraded for the same thing and the doctor that inspected us, he said, where are your marks. And I told him the same thing. If I can\rquote t make it take I\rquote ll say it won\rquote 
t take. Well - whether that was a blessing in disguise or not I don\rquote t kn
ow because - he used his pocket knife, what he cut his tobacco with I think, to make four - four cuts down like that and four across, and put the stuff on, and rubbed it in with his finger. And then word came - that the whole of the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13318710\charrsid12015019 Battalion}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019  of the 5}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\super\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019  KOSB had volunteered service and that we were to go back to Tillicoultry and the 5}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\super\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019  - the 4}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\super\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
 KOSB had to come back to their battalion. So I went back to Tillicoultry. And in nine days time I was sickening with this. And I was - taken into - Stobhill hospital in Glas - in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City
}}Glasgow{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, and they wanted to - know all my particulars about how - how I'd got this, I'd got blood poisoning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 It wasn\rquote t actually smallpox you got?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
It was - I was vaccinated for smallpox but this is the - this - it gave me blood poisoning, with this dirty knife. And they took all particulars. Well in the mean time - they went to the Dardanelles, and you - if you\rquote 
ve ever read the history of the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Dardanelles{\*\xmlclose} they were mown down as they were going of the boat. My school master used to tell me that the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Dardanelles{\*\xmlclose}
 was the strongest fortified place in the world and I believe it is. Because they never got landing there, they were mown down. So - if it hadn\rquote t been for that blood poisoning I would have been amongst them. It was that that kep
t me from going to the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13318710\charrsid12015019 Dardanelles}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
. Well there was very few come back from that {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Dardanelles{\*\xmlclose} stunt.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 It\rquote s funny the way things work out isn\rquote t it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Well that\rquote s - I\rquote ve often thought about that, that - that it
\rquote s - it must have been a blessing in disguise, I\rquote ve often thought that. Well - after I got better of the - blood poisoning, I went down to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Liverpool{\*\xmlclose} and I was there for about three months.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 What were you doing there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Oh I - I was attached to - of course my battalion was away, and - they 
attached me to the Kings Liverpool Regiment, just sent you to make up - numbers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 It was just coincidence that your stepmother came from 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Liverpool{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Beg pardon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Your stepmother came from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Liverpool
{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Yes, she did. Oh I - I met - I met all
 her friends because I - used to get off - and there was one aunt I used to go and - I\rquote d got a sleeping out pass and I used to go and sleep there, occasions - occasionally.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 That was handy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 It was. So anyway we were only three months there and -
 we come up to Gretaa, where I was another three months.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 You would be able to get home quite often from there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
Well I did once or twice, but it was a good distance to - Locherbie and four miles from Locherbie to Hightae, that was like fifteen, s
ixteen, seventeen, eighteen, nineteen - nineteen miles, but I did cycle up a - occasionally when I could get a pass off. Well - as I told you I tried to transfer out of the - Kings Own Scottish Borderers, and my brother was called up and put into the moto
r transport - tried to get me to transfer into his lot from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}France{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. But it never worked, it never worked out but then - when conscription came out they didn\rquote t ask me, they called the role one morning, the Sergeant when he came to my name he says, pack your 
kit and report to the orderly room. And when I went to the orderly room they - produced a - a warrant to take me to - Grove Park in London, to pass a test for driving, and that - ended me out in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13318710\charrsid12015019 Mesopotamia}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 , so that\rquote s how I got out there, they didn\rquote t ask m
e if I wanted to transfer then. That\rquote s the way they - you\rquote re only a number in the army.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 You didn\rquote t have any bother with the driving test then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Oh no, I\rquote d no bother at all. No bother. In fact -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 When did you go out to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13318710\charrsid12015019 Mesopotamia}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Janua
ry 1916. I think it was when I went out there, and I go the job as driving the - the Officer Commanding out there. But only for a short time, until he told me when our cars come out - our cars weren\rquote 
t out when we landed there first but when they came out and we had to go and get our cars the half of the boys that were - passed and sent out to drive couldn\rquote t drive and I - I go the job teaching them to drive.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 That\rquote 
s what happens when you pick men by numbers to go and join motor transport?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Aye. Aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Were you}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7866099\charrsid12015019  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 out}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7866099\charrsid12015019  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13318710\charrsid12015019 Mesopotamia}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019  \lquote til the end of the war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Aye, to the end of the war, two years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 How did you enjoy army life then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Oh I never can say I enjoyed it. We had happy times of course, we\rquote 
d lots of happy times in the army but - oh I don\rquote t know. Army life never appealed to me.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 What was the food like?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Sometimes it was good and sometimes it was - not so good.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 You say you were driving the Commanding Officer around?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Were the officers quite easy to get on with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
Oh well V got on well with them. Got on well with them because - they broke up that company in the finish, and I was sent to a - a - a company away up in the Persian hills on convoy duty. And - I contracted }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13318710\charrsid12015019 dysentery}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 , and I came down into Bag
dad and after I got back - I was sent from Bagdad down to a place called Somara, and I was there until I got better of the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13318710\charrsid12015019 dysentery}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 , and when I went up - on my way back to my company - I was staying in the depot at Baghdad, \lquote til the time came \lquote til we got 
them grouped together to go up, and I bumped into a Captain Farquharson who was with - my company when I was driving the OC. And he says, dear me, he says, where have you sprung from Shearer? I says, oh I\rquote ve been down at Somara. I\rquote d had }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13318710\charrsid12015019 dysentery}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 . And he says, you wouldn\rquote 
t like to come down to the reserve vehicle park with me? I said, I would very much. Well he says, I'll see what I can do. Well that was going to save me going away up into the Persian Hills again because - it was - it wasn\rquote t long until the 
armistice came after that. And I thought to myself, I don\rquote t want to go away up into the Persian Hills, I\rquote 
ll be quite pleased to - to go down there. And - next morning when the Sergeant called the role, when he came to my name, he said, pack your kit bag and report to Captain Farquharson at the reserve vehicle park. So I went }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13318710\charrsid12015019 down there}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 . And - the first job I got was to go to Mosel, that\rquote 
s seven hundred miles above {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Baghdad{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, driving a - an officer inspecting dumps. And while I was there - I went - to visit the ruins of Ninevah. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13318710\charrsid12015019 It\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019  just a mound where they\rquote ve been excavating.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Had they been excavating at that time when you were there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
Oh - I - I think everybody had had a go at it. Because the bit was all - dug up. And - from there - I went across to a place called - Nabbaunis where Jonah\rquote s tomb is. And I went into Jonah\rquote 
s tomb along with the interpreter, there was an interpreter along with this Colonel that I was driving, and it was he who come to my billet in the morning, he says, are you coming for 
a walk? So this we landed out at - the ruins of Ninevah. And had a walk over there and then he says, come on, we\rquote ll go over to see Johna\rquote s tomb. And that was the place called Nabbaunis.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 What sort of pay did you end up with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Oh with two and fourp
ence - I got two and fourpence a day in the - in motor transport when they transferred me. It was a big difference as a shilling wasn\rquote t it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
Was any of your money sent home to your mother or your father, or did you get it all in your hand?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Well 
- you could make an allowance - when I was in the Kings Own Scottish Borderers - the married men had to give sixpence a day of their pay - and they made - the Government ma}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7866099\charrsid12015019 d}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 e it up to twelve and sixpence. To send home to his wife. But I wasn\rquote t married then
. And - really my pay was a little more than a shilling a day because I had passed - my shooting test and I got allowed a threepence - threepence a day for that. And after I finished all my drills and - became what they called a proficient soldier I got t
hreepence a day for that, so my pay amounted to ten and a penny altogether, I never saw the penny, I used to get the ten shillings every week. The penny went to my credit or was supposed to have done, I never saw it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Were you a private all the way }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13318710\charrsid12015019 through}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Was a private then but I was a corporal when I was out in }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13318710\charrsid12015019 {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Mesopotamia}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 {\*\xmlclose}
. They made me a corporal - to teach these men to drive. So that was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 You stayed a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13318710\charrsid12015019 corporal}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019  \lquote til you finished?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 \rquote Til - \lquote til - \lquote til I was finished, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Can you tell me what jobs you\rquote ve done since the war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Oh, since the war.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 You\rquote d go back to Mr McJerrow when you came home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 I did. It was against the grain but I did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Why was it against the grain?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Well - I thought that I could have made mo
re money but - there was so many soldiers coming home from the war and there was no jobs for them. And that\rquote s what - David Loyd George brought out the dole for, but the dole wasn\rquote t very much mark you. I can\rquote 
t just remember what it was, but anyway - Mr McJe
rrow wrote to me - to go and see him when he heard I was home. And - when I went - he asked me about - my experience in the army. And - and then he says - would you like to come back to Highfield Robert? I says, oh no, I hadn\rquote 
t thought about that, I says, you know I\rquote m married now and I\rquote 
d want more money than - than what I had when I was with him before the war. Quite understand that, how much would you want? I said, I would want fifty shillings a week, and a free house, coals and light. Dar me Robert, dear 
me Robert. They pay Castlemilk men with thirty-five shillings a week. Oh, I said, I\rquote ve got nothing to do with them, I says, however I says, there\rquote 
s no harm done and - I walked out and left him. But a letter came the next morning, he had thought the matter over, would I go and see him. Again. So I thought oh well he\rquote s going to give me what I want. And he said, well, I\rquote 
ve thought the matter over. And, he says - I\rquote m going to give you eight pounds a month, but mark you I won\rquote t be responsible for the house. Och, I says, that\rquote 
s worse than you offered me yesterday, I says, you offered me thirty-five shillings a week and a free house, coals, and light, I says, that was better than eight pounds a month, oh, I said, I wouldn\rquote t think about it, and I walked out and left
 him again. Another letter the next morning to see if I would go and - as you are aware - we\rquote 
re in the habit of closing the house in the month of August, if you and your wife would care to come and keep it aired during the month that we are away on holiday I would pay you at the rate suggested at our last interview. I didn\rquote 
t know what to do but - my wife says, oh well, she says, a cheque bounce fun - found money, she said, we might as well be there as here or staying with my father. And - it\rquote s eight pounds found money. Oh well, I says, if you want to go, I says, we
\rquote ll go. So we went. And they went away their holidays. Well the place had been neglected during the whole five years and - that I was away in the army. And the yard - I didn\rquote t know whether to get o
ut the scythe and mow it or - or get down on me knees and weed it with a knife. And that\rquote 
s what I did, and I spent three half days weeding that back yard, but - it was that causeway paying. And - with a - aye, with a piece of cement where I washed the car.
 Well after I had that done, the front - the front was all that - granite chips, but the weeds were coming up through it and I - swept the - gravel off and push - hoed the weeds and left it and put the gravel back on and did all that. Edged the drive, edg
ed all the - flower beds, cut the grass, cut the hedges. And when he come home he said, it\rquote s - he didn\rquote t know his place. But he didn\rquote t give me any more money.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 He knew fine that if he asked you to go there for that month you wouldn
\rquote t be happy looking at it in a state like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
Ayes, fine he knew that. Fine he knew that. If he had come back and seen the place as he left it - it would have been a different story. And he says, have you heard of anything Robert? I said, no, I hadn\rquote t heard of anything. Half a loaf\rquote 
s better than no bread you know. These are the sort of devils the Tories are, they\rquote re all the blooming same.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 What did you do then, did you go back to him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Well - if I hadn\rquote 
t gone back to him for the eight pounds a month as he suggested, he would have went to the Labour Exchange and said this man\rquote s job\rquote s open to him. And they would have stopped - he would have stopped me from getting the dole.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 So you were cornered really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Aye, it was a mistake I ever went back.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Where did you stay then, did you have a cottage?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
We had got a house, you remember about the house behind it - when I come off the train - it was eight o\rquote clock, ten minutes to eight when we come off the train from Edinburgh, the mail train as they called i
t, I was coming down the street and at that time they used to keep their shops open \lquote til eight o\rquote 
clock at night, and Mr Burns the saddler whom I used to - get to sort my harness when I had the pony, was standing wiping his hands on his apron and looking up
 at the clock and - when he saw me he come out and shook hands with me and - and I was carrying my kitbag, and we were walking to Hightae, so he says - he was pleased to see me and shook hands and - I said, you would - would you keep this kitbag until my 
father comes into the - town with the pony, and I says, he\rquote 
ll collect it. So he said, oh certainly. So when my father was in - they had been talking it over and they had a house empty and it was advertised to let, and he told my father - that he had this ho
use to let and he had twelve applications for it but - if I wanted it - no one else would get it. Well of course we had no family and that\rquote d be what they were looking to. They wouldn\rquote 
t want to let it to anybody with a family. So we got that house and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 So it was nothing to do with your employer at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
Nothing to do with my employer. It was nothing to do with my employer. Well I worked for four years - I - I went after him for more money once when I got the chance of a job at three pound a week. 
But it was only a temporary job, working in the woods. And I thought to myself, well - I\rquote ll maybe get a bit more money out of him if I tell him I\rquote ve got the chance of this job, don\rquote t do anything rash Robert, I\rquote 
ll think the matter over. Instead of giving me - eight pounds a month he\rquote d give me two pounds a week. It was eight pounds a year more than - eight pounds a month certainly but that\rquote 
s the way they counted things. Aye, just a fraction more. Well I worked for four years, until - one morning - I\rquote d been - 
applying for jobs in the Standard office, a number, and there were so many for each job at that time, that they just looked the one that they wanted and put the rest on the fire and you never knew where you were applying for a job. Buy one morning, one Mo
nday morning when I\rquote d come home for my dinner, a Doctor Logan from Ecclefechan had been there to see me and he was coming back. And - he wasn\rquote 
t local, he turned up. And - he says, I got your application, he says, this morning and I had to come into the town anyway. So he says I thought I would kill two birds with one stone. I want a man that\rquote ll come and stay with me, he says, I\rquote 
ve had three since the war ended, he says, and he come there for a few months and away they go, well doctor I says, they can\rquote t live on the wages that are being paid. I says, they don\rquote t realize you - people don\rquote 
t - realize what the cost of living has gone up to. And they expect you to come back from the same wage as you had previous to the war. I\rquote ve never paid wages like this in my life
. He says, I give my man forty-five shillings a week and he has a free house, an sticks, I says, It's not enough. He said, dear me, how much would you want? I says, I would want at least fifty shillings a week. I\rquote ll tell you what I\rquote 
ll do. If you\rquote ll come to me for three months, and you - for forty-five shillings a week and you\rquote re }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12787839\charrsid12015019 suiting}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019  me, after that period I\rquote ll stretch the point, I\rquote ll give you fifty shillings a week. All right, I says, there\rquote s just one other thing. I would like to see the house that I
\rquote ve to occupy. When could you come? I said, I\rquote ll come down tonight and see it after I\rquote ve finished my work. What time do you think you\rquote ll be there? About seven. I\rquote 
ll try and be there. He was a doctor and of course he may be called out. So I went down. Well you 
went up - stone steps with an iron railing to it and you opened the door and you were in the kitchen. You went to the corner - and you opened the door and you were in the second room and you went through that room and opened another door and you were in t
he third room. But it was just a - a loft divided into three. I says, no, no, doctor, I says, the house is not suitable, I says, I\rquote m just as anxious to get settled down as what you are to get someone to settle down with you. I\rquote 
m quite pleased you say that, now when he shook hands with me and when we come to the door there was some big trees. I\rquote ll cut these trees down for you if that\rquote 
ll make any difference. No, not a bit I says. Well - the next day when I went - down - at dinnertime - the - one of the maids told me that I\rquote d to have the car at the front door - at two o\rquote clock. And McJerrow come }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12787839\charrsid12015019 out lighting}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019  his pipe and - oh Robert, he says - what\rquote s the least you
\rquote ll take to stay with me? I says, I told you before. Fifty shillings a week. All right, you\rquote ll get it. Well they had been for my reference. Doctor Logan had been for my ref - reference. I says, yes, well, but, I says, there\rquote 
s just one other thing, I says, as soon as I can get a decent house, I says, I\rquote m not staying in the house that - that I\rquote m in now. So I says, I\rquote 
m not going to settle down even for that. Dear me, he says - he had the letting of the houses, in Locherbie, they built a new - housing scheme, he says, I didn\rquote t see your name amongst applications for the houses in Victoria Park when we let them.
 No, I says, you didn\rquote t. I says, did you expect me to pay a rent of twenty-six pounds a year off two pounds a week? I says, don\rquote 
t be ridiculous. What do you pay now where you are? I said, I pay twelve pound a year. Does the houses suit you otherwise? I say
s, oh I've nothing to - nothing against the houses. Well you go to Mr Pender, he was the deputy Town Clerk, go to Mr Pender, he was the deputy Town Clerk, go to Mr Pender and tell him you want the first house available and I\rquote 
ll pay the half of it. Oh, I says, all right. So I went to Mr Pender. And he says, oh, I have a woman in here every day, Robert, he says, wanting a Weir house. Away round and swap her. I says - it\rquote 
s no so easy as that Mr Pender. He said, why? Well I says, I can\rquote t go and swap her I says - Mr Budge - Gun Budge the shoemaker, he had a house - a shop in Moffat, one in Locherbie, one in Hawick and - several places, I says, I\rquote 
ll have to ask him his permission before I can change houses. Well, when could you see him? I says, I\rquote ll see him on Thu
rsday. Thursday was market day in Locherbie. So - he was the owner, he had brought the property - the year previous. So I went in to see him when I was home for my dinner and I said - did he mind If I changed houses with a - a person that was in Victoria 
Park that was looking for a smaller house and I says I\rquote m looking for a better one. Oh I don\rquote 
t mind, he says, as long as I get the rent for it. So I went round to Mrs Carruthers and - she agreed to - to have this house and we changed houses. And - we flitted round there and we lived there for fourteen years, \lquote 
till McJerrow died. And after he died - I\rquote d been twenty three years with him, and he left me twenty pound.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 When was that then, what year did he die?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 1935. So after that -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Was that you out of a job then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
Aye, I was out of a job but I got one - right away, the man that had served his apprenticeship in the same office as Mr McJerrow came after me, and he promised to make his house - he says, it\rquote s not a house like this but, he says - I\rquote 
ll make it as good as this, I\rquote ll put you in electric light and he says, I\rquote ll - put you in a bathroom And - I don\rquote 
t know what all he promised but after we went there we were only there eight months, he never did anything towards - sorting it. And one day I drove them into {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Dumfries{\*\xmlclose}
, another Tory - and they went straight to the electricity department. And the man, the porter come down the stairs, he said, who is these people? I says, they call them McMurdoch, they come from McMurdochson, up in Auldgirth. Oh, 
these are the people that wanted light put into a cottage and whenever they heard tell of the price - they wouldn\rquote 
t have it done. I says, thanks. Thanks for that information. So I just give in me notice and left there then. And I had my half day off and on
 Wednesday and when I got to Dumfries Standard here there was a place - at Crossmichael, Wallbut up in Crossmichael. Wanting a chauffeur gardener, and I thought to myself now - I\rquote ll just take the bus over to Locherbie and I\rquote 
ll get Mr Stevenson, it was McJe
rrow and Stevenson, it goes under that name yet, sell Stevenson was his confidential clerk when I was with him but McJerrow took him in as a partner when he was going to be losing all the jobs that they had when he was over aged like - the bankers job and
 - it\rquote s time you were finished? So - I went to Stevenson and I said to him I said would he - would he put in a word for me to Mr - Gillespie, Lidderdale and Gillespie the writers Castle Douglas I says, they\rquote re }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12787839\charrsid12015019 wanting}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019  a chauffeur gardener, he says, oh Robert he says, it\rquote 
s Mrs McJerrow - that should give you that reference. I says, but, I says, by the time I get word to Leatherhead way down in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Surrey{\*\xmlclose} and get word back, I says, the job\rquote 
ll be filled. All right, Robert, he says, you write them tonight your application and I\rquote ll write them, and see what it does. So I got a wire to say meet them at the station hotel in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Dumfries{\*\xmlclose}
. And - he says - he gave me what wages I wanted and - and he says, there\rquote s just }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12787839\charrsid12015019 one}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019  thing, he says, the house is not up to much, it\rquote s just a - a loft, and a step up, I says, well it\rquote s - the house is the first consideration. So - he says, oh but I\rquote 
ll make it - if you\rquote re certain suiting me he says, I\rquote ll make that house suitable for you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 You\rquote d heard that }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12787839\charrsid12015019 story}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019  before?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 I had, but - I th
ought to myself he seemed a different stamp of man, someway than - those that I had dealt with, I says, all right, I would like to see it first. He said, by all means, he says, when could you come? Well I says, it\rquote 
ll have to be next Wednesday now. All right, he says, if you come with the bus - leaving {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Dumfries{\*\xmlclose} at such and such a time he says, I\rquote ll have - my mother\rquote 
s chauffeur meet you at the bus station and take you out to Wallbut and - my wife will show you over the place and show you the house and then yo
u can decide. So I says, very good. So sure enough his chauffeur met us off the bus and we went out and they - took us over the place place and - gave us our tea, and - the house - it didn\rquote 
t seem too bad, there was only - it was all right, it was dry and everything, and she said that she would put a new range in the - wh}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12787839\charrsid12015019 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 r}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12787839\charrsid12015019 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019  was the kitchen for us. And - until we got the house sorted to my liking, there were builders in the place putting a wing onto their house. At the - at the time. Aye, so - time went on a
nd about a month or six week there and he come to me, he says, well Shearer he says, if you\rquote re willing to stay on with me I\rquote m quite satisfied, he says, I\rquote 
ll have the work done now, to your house. So - he says, come and show me what you\rquote d like. So it was a - a loose box and a stall for a horse. And - a long piece that went from one side to the other, for a harness room. So I said, well - I\rquote 
ve considered what I would like, I says, what I would like is - the half of this harness room made into a bathroom and the other half made into a back kitchen. And - he says, but you can\rquote 
t open the door and come into your kitchen here. I says, oh no, I says, I don\rquote t want that, I want a wall built here inside. And a new staircase up into the top. And a door put here, out of 
the lobby, into the kitchen. He says, you should have been an architect. I\rquote ll tell you what I\rquote ll do, he said, I\rquote ll send - what was his name - no Mr Munro - who Margaret went as typist to - I forget his name but - the name\rquote 
s just escaped me, who was architect and - joiner and architect in Castle Douglas. And he says, I\rquote ll send him out and, he says, just you tell him what you want done. And he says, I\rquote 
ll fall in with his arrangements. So he come out and looked over, he says -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 It just shows you the difference between the two?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Aye, he says, I\rquote ll - I\rquote 
ll just have done what you want done between you and him, so all the difference that he did he said, well, he says, instead of having your back kitchen here, and your bathroom there, I want your bathroom 
there and your back kitchen here. I says, quite right, I says, now that you point that out, well the back kitchen was more like being at the back, and the bathroom to the front wasn\rquote t it. So - I thought well, it\rquote 
s a good idea that. So he says - oh well, he says - I -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Can you tell me when you left Wallbut?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
Well - I left Wallbut on the second of March - 1940, that was when the war broke out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Where did you go from there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 I came to Halleaths. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 What was your job then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 I was 
out of a job for a year, at least I was out of a job when I came there, and I got a job with the Dumfries Motor Company for a - for fourteen months, driving a night taki. That was out of my line but it was just a job that turned up. And - it was really - 
advertised in the Standard - for a petrol pump attendant, and that was what I applied for. And the manager, Mr Nelson, he said, where do you live? I said, I live at Halleaths, outside Lochmaben. And - oh he says, my boy, he says, that job\rquote 
ll no suit you, because, he says, I run it in three - shifts of eight hours, and he says, some of the shifts you wouldn\rquote t be able to get a bus home, and he says I can\rquote t make it to suit you or, he said, the other ones wouldn\rquote 
t be satisfied. So he says, that jobs\rquote  - out of th
e question. But I have another job - you see - all the young people were being called up for the army, and that was - what was making the jobs vacant and his man had been called up for the army and he needed a man for the - night taxi that he had to keep 
on he said more especially for - maternity cases, through the night. And he says, there\rquote 
s also an ambulance up in the Kings Arms yard that I have to supply a driver for, twenty-four hours a day. And also in - he would have to go - to Dumfries station at a q
uarter to five in the morning and get the newspapers and take them to Mezies in Irish Street and wait \lquote 
til the - bundled them up into the special bundles, because they distributed them throughout the south - west of Scotland. And put them on the buses and the trains for the different places. And then you\rquote 
re finished for the day. And I started at nine o\rquote clock at night. And finished in time for the eight o\rquote clock bus home to Halleaths in the morning. So - we agreed on the wage that was for that job and - I thought well it\rquote 
s better than going idle so I just took the job, and I was on it for fourteen months, until the Government took over Halleaths estate for a camp. And the Major came to my door one morning about nine o\rquote clock and he said, are you Mr Shearer? I s
aid, yes. We understand you\rquote re a gardener? I said, yes. Well are you prepared to take the gardens over in the event of the gardener being called up for military service which he\rquote 
s liable to be any day? Well, I said, I think about it. He says, well let me know by Friday. So - the house was the first consideration, because if I had said no, I won\rquote t take over the gardens, I\rquote 
ve got a job, oh well, we want this house. That was the position I - I guessed, the position just at once. I said, oh well I\rquote ll have to think it over so - I went into {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Dumfries{\*\xmlclose}
 and I told Mr Nelson. And he says, oh but my boy, he says, I\rquote ve got a house for you. So - so he says, come out here. So he pointed up the steps to the house that was over the arch, you know, there\rquote s an arch into the - 
it was the house over the arch. Oh, I says, that\rquote s puts a different light on it. So I said, I\rquote ll think about it. I wanted to ask my wife if - she didn\rquote 
t mind living in the town. So I went into the office, the taxi office and there was another man, Scott, I told you about being friendly with so many Scotts, well this Tom Scott, he was one of the taxi drivers through the day, and I said to Tom, I says, I
\rquote ve got the chance of that house up there. He said, well Bob, eh says, I\rquote ve got nothing to do with it, but he says, if you come there, he says, you\rquote re night man just now and he says you\rquote 
ll be day man also if you come there. I says, thanks for the tip. I said, I\rquote ve no - I cannae work both night and day. So I decided that I would take over the gardens. And I neve
r regretted it because I had them for twelve years. It was more my line anyway, it was more my line. But it wasn\rquote t - I mean it was - harder work, but it was - congenial work. It does, it makes all-the difference and it wasn\rquote 
t - so profitable at start - the start anyway. So I took over the gardens and - it meant - oh working from seven o\rquote clock in the morning \lquote til about ten o\rquote 
clock at night. As long as - yes, as long as it was light because I had - twenty-five hens, and I used to rear chickens as well, and the - the clocks were forwards two hours at that time, and it wasn\rquote t dark \lquote til twelve o\rquote 
clock even if I had come home I couldn\rquote t go to bed because you couldn\rquote t let the hens run about and go in and out as they like or }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12787839\charrsid12015019 they\rquote d}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019  have been all - got by foxes. You 
see, there was so many foxes about, you had to have them shut in at night. So - I used to go over at seven in the morning after I had my breakfast, and - come home for my dinner at twelve. And I used to go - as soon as I heard the one o\rquote 
clock news I used to go back over and work \lquote til five. Come over and have my tea and listen to the six o\rquote clock news, and went over - and - well usually worked \lquote 
til nine or ten. There was so much to do, it was a lot of light work of course, tying up tomato plants, I had seven greenhouses, and I filled them all with tomatoes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 You were just on your own there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
I was just on my own then. And - I can remember one night I went over after - I\rquote d heard the news at six o\rquote clock. And I went to water the tomatoes because I wante
d to go into Dumfries on the Saturday, but the - troops were using water for washing at that time and there was - no water to water them with, you know, there was no - no pressure. So I screwed it off and I went and tied up a row of - sweet peas I had rig
ht across the garden, and when I finished that it was nine o\rquote clock. And I come in and I just tried the tap and of course all the troops were finished washing and there was - a good force of water and I thought well I\rquote 
ll water these tomatoes yet, so I was busy watering, and at eleven o\rquote clock that night when Margaret come in and shouts daddy. Do you know what time it is? I says, what time is it? She says, well after eleven o\rquote clock. You remember that? So -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 So you were there for fourteen years?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Twelve
. Twelve years. And - then Church worth estate Company limited came and bought the whole estate, Jardinehall Estate, Halleaths Estate, and all the ground, then were buying up all the ground they - they could get. I\rquote 
ve often said that the only real wealth - is land and labour, and don\rquote t the Tories realize this? Aye, too true they do, that\rquote s why they\rquote 
re building - buying up all the ground that comes available now. Why? Because they might - wake up one morning - they think, and the pound note\rquote s not worth the paper it\rquote s written on. And that\rquote s why they\rquote 
re buying up all the land. Well - when you think of it, everything necessary for life comes from the earth isn\rquote t it? With labour. And it\rquote s got to be produced, so therefore - all interest and compound interest on we
alth comes from the honest working man who easts bread by the sweat of his brow and you can\rquote t argue that way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 What happened when the estate was bought over?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
Well - they threw me out. They wanted the gardens - at least this is what they said, they wanted the gardens, it was the forester that wanted the gardens for a nursery for forest trees, and although I pointed out to them that it wasn\rquote 
t suitable, they thought oh I just wanted to keep the gardens myself. But it wasn\rquote t suitable because a garden like that\rquote s full of - seeds, groundsel, chicken used and I don\rquote t know what all. And - when you\rquote 
re growing things in a garden you\rquote ve got to keep these down with a push hoe and that and - but whereas - they were going to use it for these little - forest tree
s you know. Fir trees and such, to plant out in the woods. Well as a - there was a piece of ground - two acres that I had - superintended the planting of potatoes on with the troops, because every inch of ground was put to produce - vegetables, potatoes a
n
d everything - necessary, in case the - in - in - in case you - you - you were starved out that was - that was the idea, so that they - the Officer Commanding came into the gardens one morning and - he asked me if I would superintend the planting of these
 potatoes. And I said, oh well, but, I says, I\rquote ve got as much on my plate as I can manage here. I says, what about my work? He says well if you\rquote 
ll - he says, we've plenty of men to give you - to plant them and do the job if you'll just superintend it. And, he says, we\rquote ll give you - a man or a couple of men to help you forward with your work. I says, oh well, I\rquote 
ll do it in that case, I got no - money for it anything like that but I - got a couple of men, sometimes only one, but I got a - a help with my own wo
rk. And - and it was - it was a help. So I pointed out to the factor that that ground that I had grown potatoes on for several years was ideal for their nursery for forest trees, but they wouldn\rquote 
t listen to me. Well - it ended up in - seven men - weeding these trees and as soon as they got over the garden they\rquote 
d to start and go over it again, and in the finish he told the Factor, he said, well, I can buy trees ready for planting in - the woods cheaper than you can grow them in here, so they did away with - and that garden\rquote s derelict to this day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 So where did you go after that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
Well - there was a lady - came up here and bought a house - to get out of the bombing in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. And she had bought a house around Hightae, and she used to come over and get vegetables from me, out of the gardens. And when she heard - after - the war finished her husband wouldn\rquote t - come and live there because he had his business in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. And he said to her, oh, he says, I can\rquote t come up for the weekends, he says, you\rquote ll have to - sell up and come down to live in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. So the next thing she saw was the - the house advertised in the Scotsman, and of course it was sold, so she went away from here down to London, but his health broke down, and - the doctor told him - if you don\rquote 
t get out of this place and into the country for the fresh air, he said, you won\rquote t live long. And when he told his wife, she says, oh what a pity that we sold Scarefield, I had so many friends up there. He said, never mind darling, we\rquote 
ll get another place
 up there, so he wrote to some of the solicitors and he got a list of six different places and he and his son came up here and stayed in a hotel in Locherbie and went to visit one place today and another place tomorrow until they had got over and they cam
e - and they came to Newpark and saw that - and saw the river passing, he told me him - he told me himself when he saw the river going passed he said, oh this is the place for me, and he bought this place, Newpark. Well when -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 That\rquote s the one that was something to do with Bonnie Prince Charlie?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 No. No, no, that\rquote s - that\rquote s Glenstuart. I\rquote 
ll come to that. So when Mrs Chard heard that I had been put out of the gardens and hadn\rquote t a job she told him to write to me and see if I would - go to them as gard
ener. So I went down to see them and - and - we came to an agreement, it was another big garden, it was a lot of work but certainly I enjoyed it there, we were seven years there. And - I got keeping hens there too and I had my own car by this time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Did you have a cottage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
Yes, the Lodge, the Lodge at the front gate. And - as I say we were there for seven years. And - I quite enjoyed it, but - after seven years - Mrs Chard was away - in Edinburgh for a week, and there was a - retired Colonel came 
to have tea with them. And he says, do you know Chard that this was my place, he said, I would sell that cottage up there in the gardens and you wouldn\rquote 
t need to keep a gardener. So they put something into his head and he just did that. He advertised the gardens and the field and the cottage for sale, and sol it, and he came to me and he said, you needn't leave here Robert, he says, you\rquote 
ve got your car, he says, you live rent free in my house and I\rquote ll pay you - thirty shillings a week and I\rquote ll provide your - fuel and light, if you\rquote 
ll continue to keep the grass and the front. Well this was two days work, keeping the grass and the orchard and the rockery and the - the - the front - flower beds. And he thought that I would be able to get - jobs and on and aroun
d about with my car, so I thought myself that I would have been able to. So - of course - it was the house again that was the first consideration and I couldn\rquote t just say, oh no, I\rquote 
m not going to have that because I had now here to go and houses are not to be got, not yet even. So I said, all right. Well two or three days after a Mrs Jenkins that lived in Mount Annan, she heard that I was only working two days a week, came to see }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12787839\charrsid12015019 if}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019  I\rquote 
d go and work to her for two days a week. So I did. And that was four days a week. Well the man that bought the - Lodge and the gardens, he said to me he says - I\rquote 
ve no time to be bothered with all that garden, he says, if you like, it was in four plots - four big plots, if you care to have one of these plots, he says, you\rquote re we
lcome to it. I says, oh thanks very much, so I thought well I can grow vegetables to keep ourselves going. So I got this plot and - and his - it was me that really built the greenhouses that was there because I brought them from Newpark, from Halleaths. A
n
d - he bought the green - bought the gardens, the greenhouses and everything and he said, you can have this - you can have the small greenhouse, this was the greenhouse that was there before I came, but the other one, it was me that brought it there. So -
 
I said, thanks very much, so I was able to keep some plants and grow tomatoes, a few tomatoes and - and grow vegetables in the - in - in the plot to keep us going. And that was fine, but it only lasted for the summer months you see, when it come the summe
r months there was no grass-to cut or nothing to do in the gardens up at Mount Annan and they\rquote 
d no use for me, and very little use for me at Newpark, except for putting in poles and - you see, they had no grass to cut or anything. So I went to the Labour Ex
change to see if I could get some - gardening work in - in Annan, digging gardens or cutting hedges, pruning roses or fruit trees, anything. But they had nothing doing but it was when they were starting the building of Chapelcross. And - he said, oh no, h
e said, we\rquote ve nothing like that, he says, the only extra jobs we have like that\rquote s around Christmas when they\rquote re requiring more postmen. So I said, oh well, that\rquote 
s no use. But come back on Tuesday. So I went back on the Tuesday. And he was on the telephone speaking to someone when I went in, the one I had seen - the previous day. No, he says, I\rquote 
ve got no one, no one suitable. So they must have been in desperation for a man up at Chapelcross for the gates. So he ways, oh }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12787839\charrsid12015019 well}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 , hold the line a minute, here\rquote s a man just come in, I\rquote ll see what he says. So he come over to me and - he says - here\rquote 
s a job turned up at Chapel - cross - at the gates, they want a man at the gates so as to learn the different firms and where they\rquote re situated, on the site. So that you\rquote ll 
be able to direct them when they come in with the loads of stuff. Because they were coming in and going all over the aerodrome, it was an aerodrome previous, and then ending up at the head office tormenting them and they couldn\rquote 
t be bothered with them. So 
they want a man - to be at the gates, learn all the - positions of the different firms so as to be able - to direct - the - the lorries to the place. And also - keep an eye on any suspicious persons that you see moving around. He says, the wage is three a
nd nine and hour. But he says, you can make that arrangement with yourself, so I pointed out to him, I says I\rquote m only free, I says, from now, this would be in - perhaps November, end of October or November. I\rquote 
m only free from now - until March because - when March comes - I\rquote ll have to go and do the - gardens and - cut the grass for the sake of keeping my house because - houses are not available. Oh he says, I\rquote ll tell them. Oh that\rquote 
ll do fine, send him out. We\rquote ll perhaps follow him on with someone suitable in the meantime. So he says, go out and see them, so I went out the man met me at the gate. And he took me in and he says - oh, he says, this is a fine job that\rquote 
s turned up and he says - if it\rquote s not suiting you you\rquote ll get a better job out of it because there\rquote 
ll be plenty of good jobs going. Once it actually started. So - he gave me a form to fill in, well it was a book really. Where was I born. Was my father and mother - British subjects? Are you married? Yes. Is your wife a British subject? Is her father and
 mother British subjects? Well you\rquote 
ve no idea the book of questions. So after I had filled it in and signed it he said come with me, so he took me into the security - what they called the security officer, well he was really a - retired police inspector. So
 he read through the - and put his hand on my shoulder, he says, you take the job my boy, he says, if it doesn\rquote t suit you, he says, there are plenty of good jobs coming. So I said to him, oh well, I says - I\rquote 
ll have to - pack it in I said when it comes March for the sake of keeping my house. He says, we\rquote re building houses, you\rquote 
ll get one of them. So - I thought, oh well, this is going to turn out better than - anticipated. So he took me into the - the manager the head - he was the second in command of Mears
 and McLelland, they were one of the firms that had the whole contract, the rest was all sub-contracted out to the others. So when I went in this Mr Welsh - told me what would be required of me. And what sort of wage do you want? Well I says - I was told 
I\rquote d I would get three and nine an hour. Oh yes, he says, you\rquote ll get that and perhaps more, we\rquote ll see what - work\rquote 
s attached to the job. So I said - all right. And he says, when could you start? I says, oh I could start tomorrow. Oh well, he says - we haven\rquote t your hut built yet but - and he says - I would like if you\rquote 
d start on Monday, and he says, I want you to come in at half past seven in the morning because the buses all come in at a quarter to eight and you\rquote ve got to check in the men with their passes. A
nd he says, I want you to come on - Monday morning at nine o\rquote clock, but, he says, half past seven after that he says, I want to show you round and what\rquote s expected of you, and I won\rquote t be here \lquote til nine o\rquote 
clock, on the Monday morning. So I reported on the Monday morning and I sat on the place - from then 'til twelve. And the one that - had told me that he would show me round had passed it on to - the - secretary, so when I told the secret - oh I\rquote 
m too busy to be - bothered with you just now, go and take a seat \lquote 
til I am ready for you. And when he was ready for me this lets you see the red tape, he come to the door, he says, come here now, so he pointed from where he was standing right away down to the bottom of the hill, he says, there\rquote s your hut down }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12787839\charrsid12015019 bonder}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 , go and take it over. Now couldn\rquote 
t he have done that at nine o\rquote clock? Well anyway I went down - and there was another man in possession, so I said, what are you doing here? He says, oh - he says, I\rquote m - I\rquote m the checker for the - the other firm that was doing
 the - the building parts. Mitch - the Mitchell Construction Company, he was the - checker in for them. So I said, oh well, I says - the hut\rquote ll hold us both, we\rquote 
d a telephone and electric light and a - and a week electric - stove. So I said the hut\rquote ll hold
 us both fine, so - I got - doing what I did and - he did what - he had to do. Well he said there was - all I - I had to check in all the loads of stuff coming in for all the other firms except the Mitchell Construction Company, he had to do that, he - th
at was his job. However - two days - after that - the security officer landed down - and his - he says, is Mr Shearer here? And I don\rquote 
t know where I was just at the moment - oh I had been sent for to go up to the head office, they wanted some particulars. And while I was away, the security officer come down and he says, is Mr Shearer here? No, he\rquote 
s gone up to the head office. And who are you? Oh I\rquote m the checker for Mitchell Construction Company. Well, he says, you\rquote ve no business in here, get yourself packed 
up and clear out. Now, he says - I was put here and mentioned the name of the man that put him here, so he says, if you\rquote ve got anything to say go and say it to him, he says, I\rquote ve - I was - I\rquote ve got nothing to do with it, so he says, I
\rquote ll soon do that, so he went and hunted up this man and he had to pack up and go - go to another hut. So I had the hut to myself after that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 How about a house, did you get a house eventually?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 No. time went on and when it came March and I thought that - I would have t
o pack in and - and - go back to - Newpark. They - the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12787839\charrsid12015019 secretary}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
 phoned me up and he said the police had come and taken over my job in the meantime, two police. And - he said, you\rquote ll know - you\rquote ll understand that your job\rquote s finished down there Mr Shearer? I said, yes, oh, I says, it\rquote 
s all right, I says, I\rquote ve - I\rquote ll have to pack in anyway and and - go and take over my job I said, for the sake of keeping my house. Oh, he says I\rquote m sorry to hear that, he says, we\rquote d another job looked out for you. So I said, oh
, I said, what sort of job had you looked out for me? Well, he says, we\rquote re needing four men in the store, we were going to offer you that job. We\rquote re needing two men to drive the buses, they were these - mini buses you know, 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Bedford{\*\xmlclose}, two {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Bedford{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} - hold about eight or ten passengers. And he says, we\rquote 
re needing two drivers for these two mini buses. And also we need two men - for the - compound, this was all the heavy stuff, being brought in, and they had fenced off a place about two acres for all this stuff, th
is heavy stuff coming in, and they needed two men in there for to - check it in and - and keep an account of what went out. So he says, you can have your choice of any of these jobs. Well, I says, I\rquote 
ll think it over Mr Westgoth, so I thought the matter ove
r and I thought well - the job that I really would like would have been driving of one of these buses but it was - it was - another practically night and day men because the men were on duties - all hours, of course they got good pay - when they worked ov
ertime, they\rquote 
d eight hours to work, that was their - day, any hours they worked over the eight hours they got time and a third for it. But the - they were on call all the time, if anybody - living in Dumfries and working late - and no buses to take them hom
e they had to go with them. Even if it was one o\rquote clock in the morning. I thought to myself, I\rquote ll never stand up to that. So I - I rang up Mr Westgoth and I said I\rquote 
d thought the matter over, and I said - I would like the job in the compound, if he didn\rquote t - mind. So he says, I - I said what - what sort of wages for that? Oh, he says, four shillings an hour, and he says, if you work overtime at night you
\rquote ll get - time and a third. Saturday afternoons if you work Saturday afternoons you'll get time and a half, and if you work on Sunday you get double time. Oh, I says, that sounds all right. So I said, well I\rquote ll have that job if you don
\rquote t mind. So, very well. He says, I\rquote ll - I\rquote ll find you a companion. So he did, he got me another man that came from Eaglesfied, an
d the two of us had the job the whole - time we were there at the - three and a half years I was there. And - many a time my wage was - as much as twenty pounds a week, with working overtime, but I never got that much - don\rquote t run away with -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 You would lose it in tax?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Aye, that\rquote s just what it did. It just seems that the working man
\rquote ll get what keeps him the breath of life so that he can knock it out in the service of the rich.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Where did you stay then, did you keep on your house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Well -
 when I went home - and I told - Captain Chard, he - I saw him going out with his dog and I thought to myself well, I\rquote ll - cut the grass in the front and - catch him as he comes in, so when he come in it was nine o\rquote 
clock at night and I stopped the lawn mower and - and I went up to him and I says, well Captain, I said - I\rquote ve got the offer of a job - at Chapelcross. And I says, I can\rquote 
t see - that I can do his work and keep this job as well. So I says - I don\rquote t see that I should give up this permanent job for part time here. And he says, and what do you mean to do Robert? I says, oh, I says, I\rquote 
m not going to give up this job. But, he says - I says, I know perfectly well you\rquote ll need your house for someone that\rquote ll do your work, so I says, I\rquote ve bought a caravan. Oh but Robert, he says, you can\rquote 
t stay in a caravan in the winter time. I says, oh they\rquote ll have houses built by then, so, I says, I\rquote ve been promised - half promised one. He walked away and left me, just - said no more. And two or three minutes after that he
 come back out, he says, well Robert, he says - we\rquote ve all got to think of ourselves, so, he says - please yourself. But, he says, couldn\rquote 
t we get someone up from the village to help you with - the - grass and the front and the terrace and the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12787839\charrsid12015019 flower}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019  beds? I says, it\rquote s not easy Captain, I says, they\rquote re all out there from the village, earning the big money. And I says it\rquote 
s not easy getting anyone for temporary jobs like that. He says, it\rquote s these machines Robert, he says, I can\rquote t work these machines, he says, 
I had three different - lawn mowers, I had one of these cutters, an Allan cutter with a reaper blade on it. And I had a - a rotoscythe. And I had also a - an Atco mower, an eighteen inch Atco mower, the three of them. He says - couldn\rquote 
t you manage to cut the grass for me and I\rquote ll do the rest myself? I said, I\rquote ll think about it. So the next morn - the next morning or the next day when I saw him I says, well Captain, I\rquote ve thought the matter over, I says, I\rquote 
ll try and cut the grass for you for the summer months. And I says I\rquote ll - whatever time I have at the weekend I\rquote ll fill your coalbin, they had a coalbin down at the back door that held five hundredweights which we\rquote 
ve got it there at the door now, holds five hundredweights of coal, so I says, I\rquote ll fill your coalbin for you, and Tuesday morning and Friday morning I\rquote 
ll put the ash buckets out, if you can arrange to bring them in. Oh that'll do fine Robert, we\rquote ll carry on as we\rquote re doing. But }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12787839\charrsid12015019 honest it was}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019  night and day, working night and day, I hadn\rquote t a minute of
f Sunday or Saturday. There was always something to be done. So I carried on for the - for the summer months. And then - one day - when we saw the - Annan paper, ten houses nearing completion at }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12787839\charrsid12015019 Spring bells}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 , applications invited from older people. So I sa
ys why - why not put in for one of them, never thinking we would get one. So we put in for one. And - Miss Penman was the - the woman that was collecting the rents at that time, she came to visit us at Newpark, and when - she was here - my wife said to he
r, do you think we\rquote ve a chance of getting one of these houses? Oh yes, she says, you\rquote re just the very sort of people we want in them. So when I come home - when I come home at night and she told me, I says, oh, we\rquote 
ll have a chance of getting one then. So on the Sunday morning - before we went to Margaret\rquote s I said I\rquote ll take you down and see the - see - oh - see if we can see the houses because I\rquote 
d asked one of the men that I worked with to tell me where they were, well he took me to these houses down there - Standalane, and they were - nearly finished then, and - we got a word the following week to say that - they - we\rquote 
d been allotted number one, that\rquote s this one. So I said - that I would run you down to Annan to see the house that we\rquote re to get. And we went and - had a look at this that - this man had told me about. Oh and it didn\rquote 
t look near - nearly complete so we looked at the one at this end, and we thought this\rquote ll be number one. And we went - the other end we thought - maybe number one. But it was further a
way - further from being finished than the other one. I says, I don\rquote 
t think that can be the houses, so we come round and - I saw a woman shaking a duster out of the door away round here somewhere. And I ran down and I asked her where - Springbells - the ho
uses to let at Springbells were. Oh, she says, I can tell you where they are, she said, just go out of the end of that road and up to the - and turn into the right and they\rquote re in there, so we come in here, I\rquote 
d to leave the car outside there, and we walked 
in and - come along here and here the key was in the door of this place so come in and - oh said, this is like - more likely to be the place because it was practically ready for occupation. So it was then we - realized that - this was the house. So when I
 told the Captain, oh - I thought he was never going to speak to me again, it was then that he came out and said that we\rquote 
ve got to think of ourselves. Not when I was going to work up there, it was when we were coming to flit here. And - it was then that he - seemed to take offence and went into the house and come out again. And he said, oh well, Robert, he says, we\rquote 
ve all got to see - think of ourselves, so he says, let me know when we - you\rquote re moving and I\rquote ll pay your removal. So -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 So you worked at Chapelcross until you retired then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 \rquote Til - \lquote til it - no, I didn\rquote t. I\rquote 
d still a year to go before I was due the pension. When I got my notice at Chapelcross. I worked up there for a week and got no pay, that - week\rquote s pay went to my credit for - and lay 
all this - three and a half years I worked up there. And when they sent me my notice - I was - I had a work - I had to work a week - and I was due a week\rquote 
s holidays. And they put it all together as if I had earned it in one week and took nine pound ten - income tax off me. That\rquote s Tory rule again. If - if - Heath hears this - he\rquote ll have me shot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 So what did you do for your last year then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
Well - I came home and on the Monday morning we had arranged to go our holidays up - north, up the north of Scotland and - I went to the Labour Exchange and reported that I was out of a job. But I said, I\rquote m going to have my week - my fortnight
\rquote s holidays. Oh then it\rquote s no use coming here, you\rquote ve got to be available for work when you sign on. Oh well, I says, I\rquote m going to have my holiday anyway. So we went - had a fortnight\rquote 
s holidays, that year we were away up at John o\rquote Groats and away round by Dounreay, and - I come back and went and reported, and they were just like you, they wanted to ken every day and every minu
te of my life, up at the Labour Exchange. So when I come to - telling - Miss Swann - where I had been at school and where - places I had been - and I told her - I had been twenty-three years in a place in Locherbie and she looks up, my word, twenty-three 
years, she says, that\rquote 
s a reference in itself, So - she took all the particulars and - after she had finished, I says, you know Miss Swann, I told her about the - the three weeks money being put together and taking nine pound ten for income tax, so I said, I don\rquote 
t think that\rquote s fair. And she just opened her drawer, she says, fill in that form Mr Shearer and I\rquote ll get you some of it back. So I filled in the form and - and she sent it away, and - on the following Friday, I went up - you\rquote 
d got to have three days lying before you get anything - off the - National Insurance, I went up and - the man that I had seen previous says, I\rquote ve got nothing for you today Mr Shearer, we\rquote ve only been two days, he says, I\rquote 
ve got nothing for you today, but Miss Swann wants to see you. - Oh. So I went and I knocked at the door and opened it and looked in. I said, you want to see me Miss Swann? Oh yes, come in, she says, I\rquote 
ve got a grand job for you. Oh. You havenae been long. So she says, two old ladies out at Glenstuart, they\rquote re wanting a gardener, and she say, oh it\rquote s a nice wee lodge. I says, that\rquote ll do. I don\rquote 
t want anything to do with your lodge, I says, I\rquote ve been in tied houses all my life and I says, now that I\rquote ve got a house of my own, I says, I\rquote m not giving it up for all the lodges in Dumfrfisshire. OH, what a pity, she says. I
\rquote ll have to get in touch with her, and she picked up the phone and phoned out Mrs Wormold at Glenstuart and - she happened to be in and she says, oh - that you Mrs Wormold? I\rquote ve got the man I told you about in here, but he won\rquote 
t come and live in your lodge. And I could hear everything that was being said because I was just sitting - she was sitting there and I was sitting here and the telephone was between us. Oh - what\rquote s the matter with it? Oh, she says, he didn\rquote 
t say there was anything the matter with it, but he\rquote s got a house, now that he\rquote s a rented house and he\rquote s been - in tied houses all his life and he won\rquote t have anything to do with them again. Oh. Ask him if he\rquote 
ll come out and see me. So she looks up, she says, will you go out and see her? Yes? I says, I\rquote ll go out and see her, ask her when it\rquote s convenient. So she says, yes, he\rquote 
ll come out to see you. What time would be convenient? Oh between five and six, and she looks up, will that suit you? I said, 
aye. So I went out - to see her and I - the man that lived across there, he was sitting at the door when I went out to get in the car and go away and he says, where are you going? So I told him. He says, can I come with you? I says, aye, if you like. So h
e come out with me to Glenstuart and instead of taking the car right up to the front door I just left it at the gate. And him sitting in it. So when I went up here she says - grooming a dog, she breeds those golden {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
Labradors{\*\xmlclose}. She\rquote s - busy grooming one so when I went up to her - asked her if she was Mrs Wormold. Oh yes, she says. Are you the - the gardener? I said, yes. Why won\rquote t you come and live in my lodge? I said, well madam, it\rquote 
s like this, I says, I\rquote m getting older now, I says - I may - I may come and live in your lodge and I\rquote 
m able to do your work for this year, next year, maybe the next year after, but, I says, you never know, I said - when you get up in years - and then I says - comes that I can\rquote t do your work, and I says, you want your house for someone that\rquote 
ll do your work, where am I going? Oh yes, I quite understand. Would you be prepared to come and work by the week? I says, oh everything being equal, I said, I'd be quite prepared to come. So she says - well, when could you start? I said, any time
 you wanted. Well she says, my man\rquote s giving me his notice but I don\rquote t know whether he means to work a week\rquote s notice or a month\rquote s notice, but I\rquote ll see him tonight and I\rquote ll send you a postcard if he\rquote 
s leaving on Saturday you can start on Monday. So he was leaving on the Saturday. And I started on the Monday. And I only intended to stay for a year, \lquote til I was due the pension. But I couldn\rquote 
t get away from her, I was with her for many years, thirteen years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 So how old were you when you finally stopped working then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
Well, I stopped working three years ago. I tried to leave, I tried to leave, I tried to leave. And she come after me, she says, I\rquote ll give you a pound a week more if you\rquote ll stay with me. This was after the first year. She says - and she come 
in and she says to you, you don\rquote t want him - sitting about the house do you? All right, I says, all - I\rquote ll - I\rquote 
ll - stay another year. So I stayed another year. And it was just the same. Wanting me to stay on another year. But - a fortnight after she gave me the pound more, she - she says, I\rquote 
ve had a letter from the income tax authorities to stop one pound eight out of your pay. I says, mercy, that\rquote s worse than I - what I was before. Not at all, I said, I wouldn\rquote t have that. Is there no way we could get rou
nd it? So I says, well - I\rquote m - paying for my own petrol to come out here and it costs me a pound a week, so I says, if you like to pay that - and - and - put my pay back to where it was - I\rquote 
ll carry on for another year. So that was arranged. And she told m
e just to go and get my petrol where she got hers and put it down to her account, so I got that four gallons - four gallons of petrol every - every week, every Friday. Ad - in the finish, the job got really too much for me. Well I was seventy-six. And I -
 it was a big place - to keep. So I made up my mind, well no matter what she said I\rquote m going to sleave - when I\rquote m seventy-six, that\rquote s on the eighth of April. So I went and told her. She just laughed, she thought, oh I\rquote 
ll stay on again and she - that\rquote s what she thought.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Was she a young person herself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 No, she - she - she\rquote s getting on for ninety now. Aye, up \lquote 
til lately she\rquote s gone fishing away down in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Aden{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} - Weatherall, away down by Loch Harlow. Goes out shooting. And drover her car up \lquote 
til three years ago, but her sight\rquote s got bad.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 So obviously she thought you would be doing the garden \lquote 
til you were ninety as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 That\rquote s what I said to her one day, I says, you want me to work here 
\lquote til I drop down dead? Yes. She said, yes. So anyway, I made up my mind that I was going to leave, I couldn\rquote t keep that place and - and I just told her. But she - she didn\rquote 
t believe me. So when it - when I had the month up, a month up, I went up and she\rquote s smiling all over, well, Shearer, what do you want today? I says, I\rquote 
ve come for my money, I told you I was leaving today. Her face went down. My friends tell me you\rquote ve let me down. I said, what, after thirteen years? I said, only come here for a year. And so she wrote me out the cheque and I\rquote 
ve never seen her since. She said she would come and see me but she never has, but she sends us a chicken each New Year. So she\rquote 
s - oh she hasnae forgotten. Each year since we left she sends us a turkey for two years, but I think she began to think that a turkey was too much for two of us. But we took it up to Halleaths and had it, the six of us had it. Oh aye, it\rquote 
s a nice big chicken. So - that\rquote s - that's finished it and - I\rquote ve been idle since.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 You would say that the employers and workers had different interests then?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
Different interests? In what way? Oh - in life, oh aye, they were - the employers were out to see how much they could get for how little they paid you. And I suppose the workers were out to see - how much they could get for their earning, for their - the
ir - work for.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Did you ever belong to a trade union?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 No, that never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
How about the differences between craftsmen and other workers, did you notice a difference in the old days?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Well - of course if you\rquote re a craftsmen you\rquote ve served you
r apprenticeship for five years, and well you\rquote d think that they - they were entitled to a little more money than a labourer was. Because - when - when you serve your apprenticeship you get very little money while you\rquote 
re serving your apprenticeship, I know when I - when I left school I got the chance to go and serve my apprenticeship for a gardener but all that I got - all that I would have got was five shillings a week and I had to keep myself off that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 So you never actually served any time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Never. I never served any time for a - gardener, although - I mean I\rquote 
ve been gardening all my life, my father was a keen gardener before me and I had a good idea what was wanted.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 You weren\rquote 
t officially apprenticed when you were in the garage learning about the cars?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
Oh well, you could call that an apprenticeship, it was only six months. You see, I - I - I only went to - to - to learn to drive and - and running repairs, that was - changing a wheel or mending a puncture or doing - doing any - odd - repairs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Would you have preferred another type of job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
No, I think if I was - my life to start over again I would - be a gardener again, even although the wages are small. There\rquote s lots of perquisites that you get you know, you get potatoes and vegetables and - although the wage is small - you\rquote 
re compensated in other ways.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
When you were a chauffeur and gardener were you more of a gardener than a chauffeur?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Well - I\rquote 
ll tell you how it worked out that way, I was gardener from - eight o\rquote clock in the morning \lquote til five at night and he would land down from the office, oh Robert, we\rquote ve got to go to Marchbank Wood, we\rquote 
ve got to go to Murray - to Murraythwaite, we\rquote ve got to go to Denbigh. I was always on the blooming road up to nine and ten o\rquote clock at night, after he\rquote d closed the office. But - and no extra pay for that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 He could relax after his work but not you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Aye. Aye, well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Did you ever have to drive Mrs McJerrow about?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Oh yes, I\rquote d - I drove them all, yes, I had to go driv
ing - often through the day down to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Carlisle{\*\xmlclose}. I remember once - she come out and said, I want the car to go to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Carlisle{\*\xmlclose}
, Robert. I said, oh all right. She said, I\rquote m going down for a roast of beef. I said, it\rquote s an expensive roast of beef. I says - twenty-five - twenty-five miles to - to Carlisle and twenty-five miles back, I said, that\rquote 
s two gallons of petrol and the running - the - the wear and tear of the car, oh yes, she says, I know that, I know that, but, she says, it\rquote s an outing as well. So that was the way she looked at it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Just a different outlook altogether from you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
Aye. Well she was pretty well off too, her father had - had - seen to it that she was well off, her sister was - Lady Mayoress of Watford, and her father lived in Watford, I\rquote ve been down and seen the place where - they lived, its -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 She was English then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Yes. There\rquote 
s two streets goes like that, and this corner was all his place. The Shrubbery he called it, the house. And when he died - the town had built out and out }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12787839\charrsid12015019 a
nd out}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
, you know - and it became more valuable, without them doing anything to it. And of course the place had to be sold because it was divided amongst six of them. And - the - the oldest son said, leave it to me, I\rquote ll - I\rquote 
ll attend to the selling of this
. And he sold it - oh for seven or eight times as much as they ever paid for it if not more. I - I forget just what it was he sold it for, twenty-two thousand I think it was he sold this corner. And I expect when he bought it he would buy it for about sev
en hundred or seven hundred and fifty. Now that\rquote s - that\rquote s - that\rquote s how - these properties - increase in value, not by anything that rich people do, but by building out and the people building out and making it more central, that
\rquote s how it becomes more valuable. Don\rquote t you think that\rquote s where they should get their taxes from? Instead of taking it off me that\rquote s working - eating bread by the sweat of my brow?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 What sort of size was Highfield, what kind of house was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Well it\rquote s - it\rquote s what\rquote s the home
 in Locherbie now, Benriach, you know Benriach? Well it\rquote s as you go into Locherbie, it\rquote s on the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12787839\charrsid12015019 left hand}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019  side. It\rquote s a good big villa. Had a - billiard room and a nursery for the children up above. Had a dining room, and a room and bathroom up above that. 
And a kitchen, and - a room and bathroom above that. And - the back room, what you call the breakfast room, it was like - back from the dining room, back from the dining room and then there was a hall and the staircase off, it was a good big house. And th
e drawing room too, the drawing room and a huge conservatory, this is where I enjoyed life in the conservatory.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12787839\charrsid12015019 Qu}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 ite a big garden to look after?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Oh quite a big garden, aye, had a big garden.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Were there small children there when you were working there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
When we went - the - the youngest one would be about five year old and the other one - eight maybe. Seven or eight.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 How did you get on with the youngsters then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Oh, they were away at school, no, no, they never bothered me, the
 one of them was away at school all the time. Away down in England, and the other one - she had a governess, aye, for a while, but then she went to school too didn\rquote 
t she, and she went to Carlisle to - Redgagles, Redgagles they call it, I was going to call it Greengables. A private school. And - oh no, they never bothered me. Except when they wanted the car to go a drive.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 They didn\rquote 
t come and say, I want you to do this bit of the garden today?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 No, no. Nobody did. I was my own boss practically, exc
ept when he wanted the car. Aye, that was in the 14 - 1914 war when Belgium was over run by the Germans, there was a German lady and her daughter came to stay there, but I was away in the army then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 You wouldn\rquote t be involved in that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Thi
nking of the time between leaving school and going away into the army, was there any great changes in your life, there would be, you went away to work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
Well - I was working - I went to work - 1909 I should think it was, and I worked in 1910, 1911, 1912, and then I went to Highfield and I was there 1912, 13 and 14, before the war broke out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
What about Sundays in those days, was that any different from a Sunday when you were living at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 At Highfield no, except he wanted the car.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Did you have to drive them to the church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
Oh I had all - I had - no, no, they walked to church. I never had to drive them to church, but - there was one day we had arranged to go and see my - cy - cycle down to Rock - Rockhall, and see my sister. And it 
was a lovely morning. And I always went down to Highfield in the Sunday morning, and had a - I had this conservatory with the flowers in that I had to water all the flowers and I had also an aviary, with - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12787839\charrsid12015019 canaries in}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019  it, and I went down and fed them, and - came up and we\rquote 
d arranged to go to Rockhall - when I come back up. But there was a Lord St Vigeans staying there for the weekend and when I went down Mr McJerrow come out and into the conservatory and said, Robert, we want the car at two o\rquote clock. He says
, we want to take a run down by New Abbey into Rockcliffe and round by Dalbeattie and home, he said, we won\rquote 
t keep you long. So when I come home and told you you said, well, I've looked forward to coming and I'm going myself. So she went off herself, I said, oh well, when I come back home I\rquote ll - I\rquote 
ll get on to the bike and come and meet you. But when we come out from having our tea at Rockcliffe I could see a cloud as black as ink over by New Abbey. And they were having a thunderstorm and when we come to - we\rquote 
d gone by Dalbeattie and was going back by New Abbey, and when we come into New Abbey the road were saturated, it had been a thunderstorm and the roads were wet from there into Dumfries right up to the top of Duthorld and then the roads were dry from th
ere into Locherbie. Put the car in and walked up home, and just as I got up home - the storm had come round - and we were going to get it, and I think it was the awfullest thunderstorm I ever saw because I stood at the back door and watched it thundering 
a
nd lightning there and thundering and lightning there and thundering and lightning there, just one stroke after another, and the kerb outside our door, we lived in a new housing scheme and the kerb was about - oh maybe six inches deep, the water was comin
g down the hill, past level with the top of that kerb. Onto Livingsgone Place, and I was thinking about you and I thought to myself well surely you\rquote 
ll have the sense to go in and shelter somewhere, because we knew lots of people on the way you know, and - they had had the storm that - New Abbey had got, and she thought, oh it\rquote s passed now, I\rquote 
ll away home before it comes any worse, but it - she just come into it at Locherbie and she come in, you\rquote d have thought she had - you\rquote d thrown her into the Lochmaben loch and pulled her out again.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 You say that they had visitors, did they do a lot of entertaining?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Oh well this Lord St Vigeans I think he had been a - a friend of Mr McJerrow
\rquote s practically all their life, I think they had - really served their apprenticeship together. Because - he was just - Sherriff Anderson when I knew him first but - he took over some responsible job - in the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}
}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Land Court{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and they - they made him a Lord. And he called himself - he was born in a village called St Vigeans, I think it\rquote s in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Fife
{\*\xmlclose} is it, you should know of it. It\rquote s up there somewhere. St Vigeans. Aye, well that\rquote s what he took the name, Lord St Vigeans because he had been born there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Did you have much to do with the visitors when they arrived?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Oh, I had to meet
 them at the station and take them back to the train when they were going away, but that was about all, unless we went drives with them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 About the way you were brought up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Mm hm.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Did your parents bring you up to behave towards your brother
s and sisters in any special way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
No. No, we were just - all brought up together. But of course my older brothers and sisters were away from home. There was only like - when I started going to school there was only a sister older than me, and a broth
er younger than me. There was only the three of us at home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Did you feel specially close to one or other of them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Oh my brother, my younger brother and I were always close together, we
\rquote re always together. I mean, when we went to school of course
 we had our own friends that we played with, and he was younger than me. He would be what - three - I think he - think he would be about three years younger than me, and of course he played with younger ones than I did at school, but when we were together
 at home, we never went anywhere without - the other.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
What did your parents say if another child hurt you, did they tell you to go out and hit back or what was their attitude?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Oh they never bothered about us, they - they just thought well - child
ren are children and they fall out today and they\rquote re all right tomorrow, so they never bothered.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 How were you expected to behave towards your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Oh - just - ordinary, I mean - what do you mean by that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Did you have to be extra polite?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 No, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Were you allowed to speak back?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Oh yes, I mean if you\rquote d anything to say they didn\rquote 
t object to you saying it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 What did they think about swearing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Swearing? Oh wouldn\rquote 
t - they never swore. No. If we had been known - known to swear it was - we were in trouble but - we - in these days you didn\rquote 
t think about swearing the same. I mean the children today are - oh they can let out a string of oaths that we never thought about in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Of course they hear it more don\rquote t they, youngsters nowadays?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Aye, and - I know, yes, and - and children playing - I don\rquote 
t know where they hear it nowadays but - I don\rquote t know, they seem to pick up swear words and - and - and - and - don\rquote t think anything of them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 So you don\rquote t remember ever swearing at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 No, I don\rquote t ever remember getting punished for swearing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Do you remember getting punished for anything else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Oh aye. I got punished.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 What kind of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Well - if you\rquote d been doing anything - and unu
sual - you got a good strapping for it. But I mean after it was passed it was past. But you got strapping at the school too. And I got many a strapping at the school, that I thought that I wasn\rquote 
t entitled to. Because when the - the teacher, Mr Sinclair was
 marking the register he used to say, point to one person, tell who talks. Well there was a - a - I can always remember there was an Ireland girl shouted my name out and he told me to come out, and I hadn\rquote 
t been talking, and I had to come out and stand on a - a from you know, there was these forms like seats. And they were all along the front, and I had to stand on there \lquote 
til - Mr Sinclair - marked the register. And then he came along with a cane, it was a long cane that they had. And I remember doing that when he hit me and he just come round my legs with it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 So you thought that wasn\rquote t fair then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 I thought that wasn\rquote t fair, I - on that occasion, that\rquote 
s why I think I always remembered it. Because I hadn\rquote t been talking.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 You don\rquote t remember ever
 being punished at home and feeling that it wasn\rquote t fair?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
Oh well - just once. Once. It was a Sunday. I got a proper thrashing that day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 What were you doing that you shouldn\rquote t have been?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Well - the meal was made on - on the Saturday, broth,
 there was broth made on the Saturday. And I was left to heat it up and boil the potatoes while they went to church, and they brought a Mr Young home with them for - for his dinner. And my stepmother - jumped on me when she come in. And she says, that
\rquote s not the way I told you to do it. It was - I can\rquote t remember what it was, it was the spoons, two spoons put in the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12787839\charrsid12015019 centre}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019  of the table, one - that way and the other that way and the salt and pepper put in between them. It hadn\rquote t been right to please her, and I
 said, oh do it yourself. And I ran out at the door, and my father ran after me and took me in and took me up the stair, gave me a - thorough thrashing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 You reckon that was for telling your stepmother to do it herself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 To do it herself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Rather than doing the spoons wrong?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Aye. Rather than going and sorting it and saying nothing I expect.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Did your stepmother ever punish you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
No. Never. She always told my father, she never thrashed us and never - well father wouldn\rquote t have let her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Do you think if it had been your own mother it would have been different?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Oh now that\rquote s - that\rquote 
s a question you can hardly - hardly answer that because my mother died when I was three years old. And - well I don\rquote t know - I can\rquote t say I ever
 liked her, my brother Richard never said he liked her. My sister Janet and my sister Nellie - thought there was nobody like her, until they fell out over the shop and my - oldest sister left home and went to keep house for a gentleman. And I don\rquote 
t think she cared much for her after that either. But Nellie - always seemed to be the favourite, well - she was always at home, she looked after the shop and post office. And she was always at home. And I don\rquote 
t know that she was thought of any more than the rest, but it seemed that she was. It seemed that she was the favourite. But I never envied her, none of us - ever envied her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 How about your father, did he have a favourite amongst you do you think?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Not in my day, I had a brother - died - I can\rquote t reme
mber him, and he was called for my father. And - when he died my - I heard my father saying I would never have another favourite. He would never have a favourite after that. It was a funny thing, the - the daughter that was called for my mother and the so
n
 that was called for my father both died young. So whether that had anything to do with him saying that I - he would never have another favourite, but I mean he was good to us all, I - I remember - he used to go to market on the Wednesdays to Dumfries and
 I - he never went a time to Dumfries with what he brought me something, when I was - when I was small.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 He would bring something for each of the children did he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Well I can\rquote 
t remember - Richard - getting anything, he was - younger. And - I don\rquote t 
know whether I can call myself the favourite at that time but - I was the one really that - got something every time he went to Dumfries, he brought me a ball or a mouth organ or something like that. Just a - but something. I can\rquote 
t remember whether Richard got anything or not, probably he would - just that I don\rquote t remember.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
Was your father the sort of person that you could talk to, if you were worried about something could you go and ask him to help you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 I never remember being worried about anyt
hing. Richard and I used to settle things out for ourselves. And - always when my father was at home we were working with him, he used to be always digging in his garden or doing something and we were always there helping him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 You must have got on well with him then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
Oh we did. Both of us. Better with him than with my stepmother - why - why I don\rquote t know, but - it - it was - I\rquote ve often it\rquote s just the idea that no one can fill a mother\rquote s place, something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Even if you haven\rquote t known your mother for very long.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
Do you think your parents brought you up to consider certain things important in life? Was there something that they would maybe always say you must never ever do that or you must always do something else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 No, I can\rquote t remember that they ever \endash 
 insisted on anything like that. Al - always told us when we were going away, now behave yourself, that was always your last - word, that was it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Do you remember going on any outings with your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Did you go into Dumfries shopping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
When I was - when I was small, no. I - when I was small I can remember - my father taking us into Dumfries to see the procession of Barnham and Bailey\rquote s show if you ever heard tell of that. Yes, a big
 circus, well they had a - procession through Dumfriesshire. Through Dumfries, the town of Dumfries, and I can tell you yet where I stood, or where I was with my father then, where he held me up because the - the streets were lined and he held me on his s
h
oulder, I was small, and it was just - a little down from the Kings Arms yard, you know the way you go into the Kings Arms, well it was just a little down there and of course the circus come down and went down Nith Place and - and I got a good view of it 
and it - it was - something I remember - seeing all the - animals in their cages.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 It would be quite something?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 It was. It was really. In - in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Did you just go with your father or was Richard there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Oh he was there too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 And your stepmother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
Yes. And my sister Nellie, too, the whole five of us. All went, we lived at Well Green at that time, if you know where Well Green is, do you know where - as you go out the middle road to Glen Caple? You come to - an entrance int
o the - Crichton, well a little further on there\rquote s a small village they call Cherrytrees, and a little further on there\rquote s three or four houses together and a lane down, that\rquote s Well Green. And a little further on there\rquote 
s a lane down to the New Queay. And opposite there\rquote s another gate into the Crichton.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 That\rquote s when you went to Brownhall school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Exactly. Yes, that\rquote 
s right, when I went to Brown - well I was just - we left there when I was - perhaps six year old or seven.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 So you must have been quite young when you went to the circus?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
Oh yes. And - then there was the Rood Fair, they used to take us into the Rood Fair and - in September.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Would your stepmother go to that as well, or did father take you on his own?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 I think he took us on - on - on our own, Richard and I, I don\rquote 
t think she was interested in fairs. And he - took us in and - took us all round the fairs and - got a draw, and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 A what?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12787839\charrsid12015019 A draw. They had - draw a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 t that time, that you could - pay a penny and put your hand in a bag and get something out. Ah well they don\rquote t do that now, instead of that they have hoopla.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 What sort of other things did you do at the fair?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Well - riding the hobby horses and - but I don\rquote 
t think I was ever - very fond of the swings, but - these round abouts you know, we used to go on that. But there - there weren\rquote t so many - I - I mean they\rquote 
ve invented a lot of different things since these - these - roundabouts and that and these - what do they call them, these - little carriages or cars. Dodg\rquote ems, that\rquote s it, well these weren\rquote t - they didn\rquote 
t have those, there - oh there weren\rquote t nearly - so many - things in those days as there is now. And if there was - I can always remember - Biddles Ghost, we went to see that. I don\rquote  suppose they have it now, Biddles ghost. But I\rquote 
ve seen it since I was grown up, they had it - it\rquote s not so many years ago since they had it. Twenty years maybe. Mention, Biddles ghost. Aye.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Did you ever get away for holidays at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Not for many days at a time
, we - went days - I can remember going a day to Dalbeattie several times.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 With your father again?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
No. With my stepmother. No, he would be at his work, and - she had - relations - in Dalbeattie. And we used to go - and see them for the day. But there was the train that - we went by train those days, of course the railway\rquote s done away with now.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 That would be an adventure?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Oh that was an experience in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Do you think that\rquote 
s how your father met your stepmother, when she was visiting relations at Dalbeattie then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
No. My father worked for some time he was out of a job and he went to Liverpool and got a job in Liverpool and he lodged - he lodged with her parents, and they all got friendly and - for years they - kept revisiting them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 So he had known her for quite a long time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Oh aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 You sometimes went down to Liverpool too didn\rquote t you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
Not me. No, Richard did. Richard went because they were - they had to - they had no - railway fare to pay for him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
How about going to buy clothes and things in Dumfries? Who would do that, would it be your stepmother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Oh aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Would you go with her to do that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 We\rquote 
d go with her to get boots or - and clothes. Usually to the - to my - what was McGowans in those days. On Plainstones, where Binns are now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Did your parents think it was wrong to do any work or play on a Sunday?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
Oh we never did any work on a Sunday, we went to Sunday school on the Sunday and then went to church when the Sunday school come out. And we had our good clothes on and - we weren\rquote t allowed to do anything that would dirty our good clothes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Were you allowed to do things in the house, say it was a wet afternoon?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 On a Sunday? Oh no, we had to read. We always got a vers
e of a psalm or - or something to learn. If - if it was a wet day, if it was dry we could go for a walk.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Would you all go together or just the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
Oh - sometimes we went ourselves, Nellie and Richard and I. We preferred going ourselves, we felt freer anyway.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 You said your father was interested in politics quite a bit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Oh he was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 And he went into {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Dumfries{\*\xmlclose}
 to vote that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
He did, he walked - to his work four miles and four miles back, and then when he was sitting at his supper Mr Armstrong that had a small farm just beside us, came in and said, are you not going to vote Davey? Yes, just wait \lquote 
til I get my supper and I\rquote ll go, and the two of them walked seven miles into {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Dumfries{\*\xmlclose} and the seven miles back to give their vote for Molteno. He was the candi - Liberal Candidate at that time.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 What about your stepmother, was she interested in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Oh no, she didn\rquote t go voting, she - no, no, I can\rquote 
t remember her ever bothering to go voting.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Of course she maybe wouldn\rquote t have the vote then if you were young?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 You\rquote re quite right, she wouldn\rquote t have the vote, it\rquote 
s just this last few years that the women have got the vote. It\rquote s not so awful long ago.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 After you had left school and started working were you inte
rested in politics at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Me? No, I can\rquote 
t say I was awful interested in - politics, the only thing was that I was a Liberal. I had a feeling towards the Liberals.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Following your father were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Well - Dumfriesshire was a very strong Lib
eral constituency at that time. And the majority of the children at school were Liberals.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Would you talk about that sort of thing at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
Well - I think - it would be the - their parents that were Liberals and they - they would think they should be Liberals too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Was your father interested in sports at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Fishing was the - only thing that he ever -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 I suppose being out in the country he wouldn\rquote 
t be able to take part in much other sport?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Of course foot - football hadn\rquote t the grip on people it has today.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 He wasn\rquote t a betting man?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
No. No, he - he - no, no, no, he never - never was a - I think he was interested in - green bowls, I remember I used to go with him to the green bowls at Moniavie.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 That\rquote s outside bowling?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Yes. Yes. Yes, that\rquote s right. It\rquote s not carpet bowls, it\rquote 
s green bowling, on a green. He was interested in that, but I think he was more interested in fishing than any other sport.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Did he like to go away by himself rather than mix with other p
eople do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Oh as - when I got bigger Richard and I used to go with him. And we hadn
\rquote t fishing rods but we had a - a hazel wand, with a penny - line on it and a penny bait hook, and worms on the hook, and we used to catch lots of fish, but - 
when we were by ourselves it was eels we fished for. We fished a lot of eels. My father - hated when he got an eel on, he - he liked to get trouts or hirling or salmon, when we lived at Hightae. I knew - I remember once he caught seven in one day, seven s
almon, and I caught one. I was home on leave from the army. And he asked me if I was - had any notion of going }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10230972\charrsid12015019 d}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 own to fish and I said, oh aye, so I had a fishing rod by then. And we went fishing and - and he caught seven that day. And I caught this one, an
d - oh when I got it on, oh - he was afraid I would lose it and he come to me, I\rquote ll - I\rquote ll land it for you, no, no, I says, I\rquote ll land it myself. And it was twelve pounds. It was. About - that length.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 You would eat well that week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Oh well I mean - salmon\rquote 
s a thing that if you get one feed of it you don\rquote t want any more, it\rquote s - at least that\rquote s what I feel about it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 I like a bit of salmon.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
Often? To tell you the truth - no, well once did me, I would rather have it out of a tin. You would too wouldn\rquote 
t you? Rather than - my father used to send us a piece of salmon like that when he caught them, when we lived in Locherbie, after we were married. We used to have one feed of it and I expect it was given away after that. It\rquote s so rich. I\rquote 
d rather have a - a - a - I would rather - rather have a - piece of filleted haddock than any of them. Yet. But a trout\rquote s very nice.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 It was all legal was it, catching your salmon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Oh aye. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 You didn\rquote t do any poaching when you were a youngster?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 No. No, no, we never did any poaching.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
Thinking back to these early days again did you ever get to go to concerts or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Well -- there wasn\rquote t the concerts that there is nowadays, there wasn
\rquote t near so many concerts.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 M
rs Shearer was saying that she used to go to shows that they had in the village hall?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
Well - oh occasionally but - it was very seldom I remember anything - like that, in my younger days before I left the school, but - after I left school there was lo
ts of things I used to go to. Well, you remember that - lot that used to come to Locherbie, they called the Geggie. The Geggie Thea - the Geggie, it never got anything but the Geggie when it came to Locherbie and it used to come periodically. And they use
d to put on plays - like - East Lynn and - what was the other ones they put on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 What about the Murder in the Red Barn, did you get that one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 No, I never saw that one. Perhaps you saw that one but - 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}East Lynn{\*\xmlclose}\rquote s the one that I remember most. And - 
they used to have a different one - they - they would come and - put up their - marquee for a week, and they would have a different play every night for the week. And you could go every night if you liked because it was - sixpence to get in just. So - whe
n
 it was there we used to go to that. And then - this was after I left school of course - concerts and things used to come to the Town Hall in Locherbie, for instance there was one night Scott Skinner came. And my father and you and John and Tom - all went
 to it. I have a -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 How about dances?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 I never was a dancer. I never - dancing never appealed to me some way, I don
\rquote t know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Did you never go to dances just for the company?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 No. No. Never bothered going to dances some way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 What other kinds of things did you do in your spare time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Well - I went fishing in my spare time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Anything else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 To tell you the truth I - work seemed to be a contin - a contin -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Did you make new friends when you started working?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Oh }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12787839\charrsid12015019 aye}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 .
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Did you find people to go fishing with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Oh yes. Oh yes, I\rquote 
d - friends that I went fishing with. But - these - these - these friends all }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12787839\charrsid12015019 seemed}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019  to have passed on now, there\rquote s one - Walt Bethel that I used to go fishing with, and he\rquote s - dead, and - the best friend I ever had - was killed in the Dardanelles.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 These were boys that you met at the farms were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 How often did you go back to your home after you\rquote d left to start work?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Well on the Sundays, I used to get home on the Sundays, that was all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 You managed to keep in touch with all your brothers and sisters then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
Well - some of them were away long distances, for instance my brother Jack was away in Ellensburgh, my brother Willie was in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Glasgow{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. My brother Ji
mmy was in Inveraray. My sister Janet was at Balloch. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 It\rquote 
s difficult to keep a family together once you all go away like that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 That\rquote 
s right, that's what the - poem says, they grow in beauty side by side, they fill the home with glee, but they\rquote 
re graves are scattered far and wide by mountain stream and sea, so that - I think that happens with the most of families. They get - spread about.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9711576 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 
When you went back home on Sundays did you ever take any of your friends with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3887919 RS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9980725\charrsid12015019 Well any friends I had at that time weren\rquote 
t interested in going with me, they were anxious to go and see their own parents because that was the only time we got.
